Special people come into your life... people, when you‚Äôre young, who realize you aren‚Äôt comfortable in your own skin so they‚Äôll let you climb on their backs until you‚Äôre comfortable enough to stand on your own.  People who give you a nickname that survives the test of time.  Sean, you were one of the first friends I made when I moved to Milford in third grade and I can't tell you how much I appreciate everything you did for me. You were such a special person, the guys and I are better people just to have known you and call you our friend.  I'm so grateful for the last few conversations we had and the time we spent together.  Your strength and acceptance was inspirational. I'll cherish that last hug we shared.  It was an honor to call you a friend but you know you‚Äôll always be a brother to me.  Till we meet again bro, love you.

Yesterday, Ian had an issue with his insulin pump, leading to him having no insulin in his body for an extended period of time, leading to diabetic ketoacidosis. 
This is a scary moment for us, as it was this issue that sent him into the hospital in the first place, when he was 5 years old, before we knew he was diabetic at all. His sister Anika won a green hippo for him at a Village Inn crane machine during his first hospital stay, and she gave it to him then. Today, she brought it back to him. 
This time was one hundred percent different from last time, with the notable exception that it still scared the hell out of me. We knew what to expect, his mother immediately administered insulin and took him to the ER. He will be getting out today, but I'll never forget his description of DKA as feeling like "my blood was on fire." Happy to have to him safe, and hoping it never happens again.

Truth be told. I always thought that pregnancy would mean (besides many less shallow things) that I‚Äôd for once be able to look at myself without judging the extra fat on my tummy or the bum that could do with some extra squats (or any at all). Don‚Äôt get me wrong, l‚Äôm proud of my growing belly and I show it off in tight dresses. Plus, I have a lovely man (and many friends) that tell me how beautiful I look daily. Yet I look in envy at those pregnant girls rightfully showing off their gorgeous bodies online with so much confidence. While when I pass a mirror, my eyes will still firstly judge those softening areas that have nothing to do with growing a baby and everything with the cookies I‚Äôm stuffing down my face.
So, to turn this around, to look at this body with just the pride it deserves, and to create an ever lasting memory of this incredible, special and beautiful time in the lives of myself and @surfguidealgarve , I asked the grande @massimopardiniphotography to document it and make me feel pretty. Louise Mills n√©e Bahlsen was my great great grandmother. Louise was born and trained in L√ºbeck, Germany as a mezzo-soprano. She met John Henry Mills, a British merchant marine 14 years her senior and were inexplicably married at two tiny Catholic churches along the coast of Chile in 1867(!) She became a professor of music in Liverpool. My great grandfather Alfred John, born in 1888, was their only child. John died at sea around 1891.
The next records are of Louise and Alfred leaving Liverpool for Montreal on the SS Parisian in 1898. I been lucky enough to find her in many exhaustive British newspaper archives. At about 8:30 this morning, my kitty Enid died at our vet. She would have been 12 in a few months. On some level we'd been preparing for this for a while--she'd been diagnosed with kidney failure a little over a year ago--but these final few days, when things took a sudden turn, were still so shocking and unexpected. I'm thankful she's no longer struggling, and that I was with her in the last moments, scratching her cheek and head in the way only I knew how.

Over this last decade, she was truly MY kitty. When I worked overseas for a while I left her with my folks for about three months. The first morning I was back she immediately jumped into my lap and snuggled up against me, something my parents said had never happened in her time there. Beth can attest to the numerous times Enid would yowl with loneliness when I was gone, but would completely ignore her when Beth would call "hey, I'm right here!" There was only one person she truly wanted, and I'm glad I got to feel her soft fur one last time this morning.

Tonight we said our final goodbyes to our sweet Chelsea after doctors discovered a cancerous mass in her stomach which could not be safely removed. She was my four-legged soulmate, our little protector and Eisley's best friend. Chelsea was with us for almost 8 years (she would've turned 11 in October); always there wagging her whole body through some of the toughest times I've had and made the best times even better. She's survived by her sister Ava and three humans who will forever love her. We will miss you so much sweet girl.

Friday was Eisley's last weekday at home with me before starting Kindergarten. On our last day together Judy (she's a fantastic wife and mom btw) told us to go do something fun. We bowled, she got three strikes and beat me (I came back strong though), we played games and I won her a unicorn. This was the most-amazing summer of my entire life. I'd be lying if I said it wasn't without its challenges, but those were few and far between. I'll truly miss my favorite little human being around all the time but I'm so proud of the little lady she has become. We finished up this evening by making a board showing a few of the fun moments we had these last 2+ months. Before I tear up too much I'll just say this: being a dad is the best thing this world has to offer.

The lovely daughter got a smaller bike for her birthday two years ago but never showed much interest in riding a bike until this summer. As kids do she grew substantially in the intervening two years and honestly needed a new bike. That said, we parents would not be duped into buying another bike only to have her not ride it. So we told her she "might" (wink, wink) get a new bike for her birthday if she learned to ride the smaller bike. Well, ladies and gentlemen, she worked and worked and learned to ride that tiny bike and on her birthday she received a new bike and loves it (especially the fact that it has pegs because she's a huge Napoleon Dynamite fan). The moral of the story is that parents still have power, kids do enjoy things other than staring at a smartphone screen and one day, if she works real hard, she might just take her new bike off some sweet jumps.

Exactly one year ago today we flew international GCM > YYZ > YOW. 

Grand Cayman is a major cruise ship port. While we were at a museum in George Town, my husband remembers people coughing near us. At the time we didn‚Äôt know much about the virus that was quietly making its way around the world. A week after we returned home our workplace doors closed for non-emergency access, and we started working from home shortly after that. I had a terrible cold for a month. The health line nurse told me my symptoms did not match the requirements for covid testing and I probably just had a cold. Forever a mystery (no antibodies test)... did I have it? Maybe not? One thing I am sure of, looking forward to the vaccine jabs. 

This photo has nothing to do with that story. These littles wait patiently for me to finish the day job hours. My studio and office are the same place and I am surprisingly able to keep the two separate. Unfortunately my studio time hangs out on the back burner more than I‚Äôd like. I‚Äôll get to you guys someday!

Meet our wine director, Andy Miller, from Venice, CA

‚ÄúI was touring playing music for a living in the past and would always look for new local craft beer to try. From that it quickly turned into finding new wines. Natural wine wasn‚Äôt a thing I was aware of at the time until a few of my older friends caught onto this little bar in Los Feliz - Bar Covell. It was the first time I had wine with varietals I was familiar with done in a totally different style. The wines were fresh and bright, acid driven and slightly funky. 

A few restaurants and cocktail bars later, I began working at a natural wine bar where my mind was blown by everything we carried. Grower producer champagne, old skin-contact wine from Georgia, hybrid grapes from the northeast and everything beyond. 

I‚Äôd love to pour you something special and chat natty wine next time you‚Äôre in!‚Äù

Isolation Project: Self Portrait

For our second isolation project we were tasked with taking a self portrait. 
In the portrait we should include something that has been with us in isolation or that represents our isolation. 
I chose emotion. 
Our emotions are always with us and I‚Äôve taken the time during isolation to try and really understand my emotional state and acknowledge it. 
What you see is a story, starting with silliness flowing to boredom, depression and anger. 
Then follows acceptance and a will to take charge of an emotional state. Which then evolves to seeking support from those around you, leading to light and happiness. 
I‚Äôve included the before images and the final edited images. 
To make the edits I used Affinity Photo for iPad. 
In the images I used a darker colour palate for the ‚Äúnegative‚Äù emotions, which get gradually darker and grainier as they progress. 
As the emotional state moves into a more positive mental state the images get lighter, brighter and the light becomes more intense. 
All photos where taken using an iPhone 11 Pro Max using the wide lens, the iPhone was on a tripod using a remote shutter and the light is provided by a large window for ambient light and an additional adjustable key light. 
For the record I think it‚Äôs important to not think of less desired emotions as ‚Äúnegative‚Äù. While they can feel that way at the time it‚Äôs important to see that without them we would never feel happiness. We all have dark times, it‚Äôs good to acknowledge and accept them and to deal with them. 
#mcrisoproject

11 years ago today I lost my dad. That moment in time obviously changed my life. I will never be the same. I gained a new perspective that day. I knew I never wanted to leave my kids as young as my dad did.
*
I know that I am predisposed to certain diseases from my parents. I could have laid down and waited for the time to come when they got me too. I certainly was grieving and depressed enough to stay stagnant. I made the choice right then to outrun my genetics.
*
I have been most recently working on an Ultimate Portion Fix Master Coach  certification. I know there are others that want to make the changes that I did. And I want to help!

Let's talk about why we want to make changea in your lives. Tough subject? It can be. I'll go first. -

In this picture is one of my "whys" for striving for a healthier life. My kids are my world. This guy here has a rare genetic syndrome, autism and he doesn't talk. His future is always my worry. I wonder who will take care of him when I am old and can't physically do it. Scares me immensely. -

In my marathon toward my finish line I will live the fittest and best life I can. Will I hit a wall and slide smashed to the ground? Sure. With I have times where I am a super sprinter? Absolutely. Will I hit the finish line perfectly? No way.  Will I fight the entire race with consistency and intention. You betcha! -

What's your why? Think about it. Then get out there and put in the effort for your why.
Keep going. You may be someone's superhero.

Let's talk about migraine headaches for a minute. Do you get them? I do. They suck!! .

Sometimes they really cramp my style. Keep me down when I want to be out running around. Delay my days. .

Many times I have had to power through them and get my kids to the doctor or to an important school meeting. I can't skip these things. Planned months ahead. Groups gathered to love and assist my children in their learning and behavior. .

Many times headaches have gotten in the way of my ability to exercise. Doing cardio or lifting light weights with a migraine is puke worthy for me. What I have found is that I can still manage to eat within my plan and still make good choices. My gift to myself even when I feel crummy. .

Nobody is perfect. Most certainly not me. And that is ok. Every day I give myself the best care I can. The most important is that I take the opportunity to try. .

How are you going to slide around your obstacles and care for yourself this weekend? Think about it. Take the chance. You are worth it!

Determination. Do you have it? The dictionary says it is the firmness of purpose. .

Did you know that not having a plan can become your purpose? Not making a choice can become the choice you made? Not making decisions and letting someone else decide for you gives them control over your future? .

You can decide. You can make a choice. You can create a plan for your life. Instead of eating the same junk you can choose a healthier choice. You can choose to carve out a little time a day to exercise. You can plan to have the stronger body that you want. You can plan to improve your health. .

I think the first change is looking within yourself. Start caring about yourself. Nourishing your body. Moving your muscles. You will feel better, smile more, be stronger. The other things going on around you will start to change. You will see. .

Can you climb the mountain of self love? Are you determined?

Seize the day! .

How many of you are actually taking every chance you have to live your best life? How many of you think to yourself that there is always tomorrow? That you will do it later? .

Tomorrow isn't promised or guaranteed. Your time is now!!!
What people think of you is really not your business. Don't worry about what everyone else says. You do you and you will find your tribe.

I made a commitment today to get out of my own way and stop believing my own excuses. I'm going to get real. I'm going to love myself and speak to myself kindly. I'm not going to quit. This shit is getting real.

This was me the last few days. Just not feeling it. Many reasons. Won't go into that.

What I can tell you is that I didn't let my circumstances sidetrack me from taking care of myself. I ate clean, loved on my kids and did what I needed to do to love myself. I made a commitment to do my very best and not give up.

What does that commitment look like? It means not turning to junk food, like I would have in the past. It means following my meal plan and tracking my intake. It means not punishing myself if I stray from my plan. Not considering my whole day blown if I eat a cookie. Just building it in to my day and keep going. It's being kind to ME. I do it because I'm worth it.

You wanna know something? YOU are worth it too!!!

This is 45. Take it or leave it.

But I wasn't always this confident. It's taken me years of thinking what I would have said.....after the fact. I used to let people decide things for me. I would just go with the flow. Follow the crowd.

Then......I decided I wasn't going to put up with that anymore. I changed my mindset. I changed my attitude. I stood up. I took control. I started being ME!! And being me feels great!! Are you being YOU?!?

I got my emotions crumpled up and left in a big pile this week. Sending my special needs child back to school is like a kick in the gut. I should expect it by now but it still gets me.

Sending him off forces me to face our future. A future where I won't be there anymore. When I'm too old for him to come home to. When I can't take care of him anymore. Those thoughts haunt me. I can't lie. I can hide them most of the time and live one day at a time. Some days I can't.

I don't stay there long. I'm getting back up. I took a long hot shower. Cried it out a little. Getting my shit pulled back together. Things just got real. And that's ok.

Next!

One of my all time favorite pictures of these two gems from 2011.

I've been watching them interact more closely lately. In part, because they actually interact.

It's been a rough road of jealousy between them growing up. Finley gets treated differently by my ex husband for being "normal". Jasmine got special, unwanted, attention from me for being so sick growing up. Guilt, gender, age, circumstance....caused me to parent them very differently. And they are both growing up with a profoundly handicapped brother who requires 24/7 attention that causes a ripple in everything.

I am proud of them for sticking it through all the crap. They are really starting to bond and it is beautiful. When they see each other now, they enjoy each other. Finally, laughter is erupting. Hugs are being returned. Goofiness takes place. I love yous are exchanged.

It's never to late to make it better. Life is short. Love your family. Make opportunities. Don't give up! Keep getting together even when it's painful. Things can, and do, change.

Holding myself accountable. I'm in charge of me. I decide how I treat my body. I make the changes. I hold the cards. I'm the only one that can. I choose my fate.

Are you taking responsibility for you? Treating yourself the way you deserve to be treated? It's your choice.

It's December. Christmas is in less than 23 days. üò± Gifts have to be purchased. Cookies made.  Houses decorated. Parties attended. School events juggled. Work obligation met.

I'm here to remind you to take time to take care of yourself. Take that longer shower. Eat that healthy snack instead of cookies. Go for a walk with a friend. Linger around the tree with your kids. Kiss your loved ones under the mistletoe. Cherish the little things.

Don't let the business  of this time rob you of the precious moments that are surely present.

This boy is about to get the change of his little life. He has scoliosis. Before Christmas he is getting fitted for a back brace. Just in to the new year he will get that brace. He has to wear it 17 hours a day until he stops growing. That's about 4 years.

Not gonna lie. This is freaking me out BIG TIME.  We have faced many challenges together. My committment is strong. My love it deep. His stubborn streak hasn't broken me.....yet. This will be a huge test for both of us. He will resist, most likely violently. I will have to dig deep into my reserve of patience with him.

Together....we got this!!
All three of my babies were together on Christmas morning. Dream come true!!

This year I am focusing on targeting inflammation in my body. I suffer from migraines.  I experience depression and anxiety. I've been feeling sluggish and fatigued this past year. I know that inflammation can be a major factor in all of this.

I've started drinking celery juice daily. I have started using hemp CBD oils daily. I will be focusing on a more plant based diet and eliminating some foods that typically cause inflammation.

This whole search for my best life is constantly ongoing.  I know there is no such thing as a quick fix.  Slowly incorporating all the things I am learning will get me where I want to be. I am always stopping to appreciate exactly where I am though. Life IS good!!! What are your best tips to reduce inflammation? .

What are you doing this year to improve your overall health?

And just like that.....I'm the mom of two teen boys and a 20 year old daughter.

Yesterday my baby became a teenager. The big 1-3. And, it's one of the biggest honors of my life, to usher him into this period of his life.

This child is my sunshine! üåû This big smile makes every day worth living. His old soul is the sweetest, most understanding of anyone I know. He is simply the best, better than all the rest. And, I'm probably biased and I'm ok with that.

Recommitting to myself.  Had a great talk with a very important person in my life. Helped me remember that I am important and worthy of love. Worth the time. Worthy of care. And that I matter.

Don't forget, you are worthy too.

- I'm a domestic violence abuse survivor. - I went to 4 different elementary schools in 4 years. - I got married at 23 and divorced at 25. One beautiful daughter later. -I've lived in 18 different houses. The longest ever being my current home. - my dad died when I was 33.

If you go back and try to understand everything that has happened or "fix" things that went wrong, you might just end up erasing YOU.

Today my company launches a new program called 10ROUNDS. It's a shadow boxing, cardio, weightlifting, core building.....badass program. So excited to do this program with Finley here at home. Perfect timing to get some great exercise while social distancing inside.

I have a free sample, if you want to try it. Just let me know.

I got kicked out of two beds last night. First, was my own. The second was my special needs son's bed as he came to find me.  He woke up in my bed and discovered I wasn't there and searched for me.

As I sit here, with my mascara smeared from yesterday, I am tired. And, I am grateful. You see, we almost lost Ryan as a baby. He has a rare genetic syndrome called Xia-Gibbs Syndrome. He is 1 in 39 million. Pretty much a unicorn. He has complex medical needs.

I'm sipping my coffee and reflecting on the world's situation today with the coronavirus. I'm scared. I'm scared for kids like my son.  These kids are vulnerable. These kids are fragile. These kids are a reason to freak out and stay home.

My son, Ryan, is worth the potential weeks of being shut in the house. Worth waving from a distance at my neighbors. He's worth being bored and stir-crazy.  He's worth eating weird panty items for dinner. He's worth running out of toilet paper. Worth all the trouble.

And guess what? YOU ARE WORTH IT TOO!!

Life gets crazy!  Every.freaking.day. Sometimes you just have to close your eyes, turn your back to the crazy, take in the clean air and feel the sun on your face.

Times are so scary right now. Life as we knew it has changed. Our lives in many ways look like someone scribbled all over them in permanent paint. We feel like things will never ever get back to what they were before Covid-19. Did you ever think that might not be a bad thing?

I think this can teach us to shut out the extra noise that was in our lives. Help us see what holds true value. Teach us to focus on what is right. Cherish the real stuff.

Turn your back on the crazy and just breathe.

Today my personal hero turns 16!!! So blessed to have the privilege to be his mom for all these years. Has it been easy? No way! Has every second been worth it? YES!! This guy here has fought for everything in his life and overcome so many obstacles to be the amazing young man he is. He continues to surprise me with his knowledge and growth. He truly is a real life super hero. Thank you God for giving me such a gift! Mommy loves you Ryan!!!

Sometimes you just have to embrace the CRAZY!! My life lately has been just that.....crazy. And I am learning to just have to start being ok with that. So many thing, for so many of us, are so out of whack. I am just smiling and going with it.

How are all of you handling all the weirdness? Any coping skills to share?
Life and love isn't about what you gain, it's about what you give.

My baby girl is moving 4 hours away this weekend. She hasn't lived with us for a while but has been in the same area.  Always a short car ride away from me. I'm not ready. Of course, she is. Isn't that the way of motherhood? The kids are always ready to move faster than we are ready to let them go. I'm gonna miss her being close by.

Missing my girl.

Yeah, I talk to her just as much as I did when she lived down the street. Maybe even more now as they get settled. I just know that she's in a different city now. I can't just drive over in 45 minutes or less.

Growing up I didn't live in the same town as family ever. My dad worked for the government and we moved every two to three years. I didn't know that was as different because I was younger.  My parents didn't see their parents and siblings. I grew up without my cousins, aunts, uncles and grandparents. I got a new set of friends and new schools every few years. The thing that stayed consistent was my siblings and one other family, that by a miracle from God, seemed to get stationed with us.

My first and last child are 7 years apart. I always wanted them to be close together in distance and things of the heart. The love between them has finally matured and is beautiful. The physical distance is unwanted. They finally like each other.

Missing my girl!
This boy is such a bright light in my world. üåª

When life hands you the crazies, look for the calm.

The last couple weeks...ok...the last couple months...have been crazy. I've found myself needing to get back to the basics. Remembering, and doing, the things that make me happy. Hugging kittens (we got two). Eating simply and healthy. Getting out in nature. Reading more books and feeling them in my hands. 

What have you been doing to feel OK during this crazy time?

Five months into the quarantine I turned 46.

For sure one of the weirder years of my life. My baby turned 13. My oldest will be able to buy alcohol. And my middle guy, if he wasn't handicapped, would be getting his driver's license. And, like everyone with kids, we started our home bound school adventure mid-March.  It's been a strange one.

I've lost myself this year, in many ways, but also had a chance to slow down and find the real me. I've found out what, and who, is really important to who I am. And really thought about what I want and who I want to be. When the bottom drops out and normal goes out the window, it's a really good time to take a good look in the mirror. I'm working on that girl in the mirror. Working on making changes. Also, working on loving myself right where I am. I'm certain that I am where I am supposed to be right now. AND, I know that I have the courage and power to change what needs to be shifted to be where I should be in the future.

The last 5 months have been a nightmare and a gift.

In one way I am absolutely isolated in my home or car from doing anything. Having a daughter with an immunodeficiency, CVID, has kept me running scared. A regular germ can send her spiraling down hill fast and to the hospital. A covid infection would be devastating. My boy,  Ryan, and his ultra rare genetic syndrome & autism just can't handle an illness the powers of the coronavirus. And both boys have celiac disease, an autoimmune disease, and many other food and environmental allergies. To top it off, Ryan simply can't/won't wear a mask. Pretty much leaves us to drives in the country and lots of home time.

The blessings come in the time gifted to us with no appointments and no buildings we can enter. We have spent so many hours out exploring our area. State parks, new lakes, farm areas, Amish Country, Sonic happy hours, Chipotl√© to go and so much more. The hours we have spent out in nature this summer are priceless.  This social isolation from others has truly been a gift. We have laughed more and gotten dirtier than ever before. And we rescued sister cats.

As school looms close, I am trying to make sure we don't loose this free spirited time we have found to just be "us".

Have you been blessed by the slower pace of isolation?

My boy caught his very first fish today.

Just a mom brag. That's all.  He was so excited.

He named him Jerry.

To the boy they said wasn't going to make it....I'm so proud of you. You are starting your second half of high school. You amaze me at every turn. Your light shines bright in every situation. You fight so hard to be you. And I love the you that you are.

To the doctors that told me my son would not make it.....you were so very wrong! He is rocking this life in ways you never could have imagined!! You failed to see the magic in our team back then. You can't miss it now.

8 weeks ago we rescued 2 little sisters from an Amish farm. I realized I never introduced them to you formally. (They play in my stories almost daily) On the left is Cheddar. On the right is Carmelita (Carmel for short). They are the sweetest to each other and to us. Constantly playing and running through the house. Always purring and knocking everything over. We love them so very much. They sure make staying home more fun.
My mini-me. So in love with this boy!!

This is me taking in this beautiful world.

Tonight we are waiting for election results. I am reminding myself that whoever wins, it will not change me. It will not change natures beauty. It can't stifle my love for my family. It will not keep me from seeing the good in everything and everyone around me. It will not discourage me from putting my best out there.

I will continue to see the beauty in the world and I hope you do too.

2020 has been rough for so many of us. As Thanksgiving approaches this week I want to challenge you to look for the little things that bring you joy.

Listen for the bark of your neighbor's dog that reminds you that you aren't alone. Cook something you love to eat, have seconds and don't count the calories. One meal won't derail your diet. Chat with your distant family, on the phone or maybe zoom, and listen to the goofy stories carefully. Purposefully find the joy!!

This year I'm having the usual small Thanksgiving with just who live here in my home. And I will eat that second helping, be extra goofy and make the best of this weird year.

Find your joy.
My baby is 14!! I still can't believe how fast time flies. I love you little dude!!

You caught me.  I've been struggling. This winter has been taking me down hard. Harder than I imagined it could.

Cyber-schooling a special needs child is so much harder than I thought it would be. Getting on Zoom 27 times a week, at 30 minutes each, is wearing me out. I have to be present, engaged, interactive AND getting Ryan to do the same. I'm his voice for the speech therapist, hands for the physical therapist, eyes for the vision therapist, hands for the occupational therapist and his everything for his core subjects. His teachers are incredible. Simple fact is.....they aren't here. They are magical directors but ultimately the work falls on me. I'm drowning. Breakfast, lunch, dinner, snacks. All fed to him one piece at a time. He isn't potty trained. Doesn't have the ability yet. It's a lot to manage.

I'm working on finding my way out. And this isn't a complaint. I'm sure most of you have experienced similar things this year. Just acknowledging that it's kicking my tail.

 My 16 year old "toddler" is fighting so hard every day to grow and learn and I am doing everything I can to help him blossom. It's just hard work. He's TOTALLY WORTH IT!!
The snow was absolutely beautiful today.
Winter is almost over. Hints of Spring are starting. The sun is out. The temps are rising. My smile is returning. My hope is increasing. Bring on the warm weather.

There‚Äôs a spot along this ragged curve of seacliff where an incoming wave hits it and then its energy radiates back out at an angle‚Äîstill in the form of a wave‚Äîand meets the next wave in the set at an acute angle. Where the lines meet, an extraordinary pyramid forms precipitously, rising to a vertex much higher than a regular wave‚Äôs peak crest. It‚Äôs shocking to see, especially the first time one sees it. So of course I have an idea for an image at this same time of day, but it requires some risk‚Äîof going down to the level of those rocks, but at a place secure enough where one can‚Äôt be swept out by the largest wave of the set. I‚Äôm not sure a mere iPhone camera can capture what my mind‚Äôs eye is seeing, but I can try. Will be monitoring the surf reports for the next couple of weeks or so, as this photographic attempt will require a substantial swell. Must also take note of the tides, as the highest tide will surely preclude this attempt. The season‚Äôs approaching demiurge bade me look, but obliquely. The voice in my head signifies that I am either a really good listener‚Ä¶ or am rather quickly devolving into the lunacy of my nether years. ::chuckle:: She has a way of conveying to me what is obvious in sublime fashion; but, also, getting me to see the subtle nature of things in language so pedestrian as to be instantly missed. < because there are days that call for sliding consciously into the limpid black: this day being one of them. The memory of The Eleven seems fading even now, less than a week later. But this stands to reason. It is reason itself: way past the time when this place lost its collective soul; when, after the cold-blooded murder of 20 elementary school children, it said that this was okay, that nothing needed to change, that insanity itself was acceptable to live with. Nay, welcome. It stands to reason. And so days like these arrive, year after endless year, in which souls are remembered, souls young and old, souls quickly forgotten, like the ghosts they are. Dusk now, and as ever the time calls forth ghosts. Once upon a time, I would come here and commune with koholƒÅ, who would be arriving in the islands this nether time of year, prefigured by their song. Crenellated, textured like the folds of a brain, this mysterious, filigreed music would envelop me, as I hung in perfect equilibrium a couple dozen feet down at the dark far edge of the reef, listening, accepting, holding my breath for as long as it took to find the sound, melt into it, vanish into liquid molecules of vibrating, egoless, everythingness.

Around me the sharp, stark call of the ae‚Äôo, sweeping and gliding in arcs and angles above the shallows, as they feed and hunt in the incipient morning. Quite soon, it will all be over: these contrasts‚Ä¶ of shapes and fields, planes and perspectives. It was worth it, walking here in the feral darkness of dawn then to sit on my haunches and wait. In an instant, then, the light.
On an embankment of pohuehue‚Äîwhere I sat to meditate, to wait, to see.
Then, the road away... or towards.
Daybreak, Kealia Pond. Last of November.

For a while now, I have imagined my body's final disintegration to be witnessed‚Äîyes, likely provoked‚Äîby benthic creatures and organisms... somewhere on the angling deeps by this island. (As far as bodily denouements go, that is not such a bad outcome, is it?) There I will be, a train of still-intact cells, molecules, atoms... sinking down slowly, gently into oblivion. Once upon a time, life began; once upon a future, it will end. In the middle of all that, everything; beyond the bookends, nothing. Or so we think... but do not know.
Man with pole walking on glass towards an early morning rendezvous with fish which, when caught, he will‚Äîpresumably‚Äîdescale, disembowel, roast, eat. At Ma‚Äôalaea Beach.

Just the one‚Äîafflicted‚Äîindividual today. As I stand here watching Venus dragging KƒÅne angularly upwards with her invisible tether‚Äîsee the diamond pixel above and to the right of the scimitar moon‚ÄîI find myself curiously stricken. The feeling is impossible to articulate properly, so freighted and fraught it is with everything. So I will let this image suffice, to remind me of the moment ‚Ä¶ and the magnitude of things-as-they-are. These things will have to be cryptic for now, for reason. In due time they will be clear enough; and, as I contemplate the pastel skyscape of subtlest light playing on the transparent scrim of the sky, I reckon that time to be precious indeed. {Once upon a time, there was a boy. Born into an archipelagic life, he found himself strung into a myriad of histories, as befit his existence in a skein of islands large and small. Once upon the future, he would find himself settled on just the one island and, with that settling, find the singular resolution to the many, ephemeral, stories.}

After-church lunch, after a leisurely drive along the north coast‚Äîam house-sitting in Far Haiku for Shay and Ian, who are in London with Kean and Liam‚Äîwas at the food trucks in the Haiku Marketplace. Satrang, today, for some awesome Indian food.

I didn‚Äôt think I could enjoy Harpreet and Jason‚Äôs food more, but I was quite mistaken. As he gave me my usual combo plate of palak paneer, organic chicken curry, lemon rice and naan, Jason asked if I wanted some cumin hot sauce with it and, as I hadn‚Äôt had this sauce before, I said sure. (These enterprising young chefs have gone just beyond purveying food from their truck and expanded into sauce creation, with their Chutney Swamy Foods collection. Currently, they have three: Tamarind Sauce, Sweet Mango Sauce‚Äîboth of which I have, and this new Cumin Hot Sauce.) I dotted each item in the combo plate with a couple drops of the cumin sauce and, after but a couple of bites sat there in the crimson shade totally flabbergasted. It was an incredible, absurd revelation.

Already bursting with flavors both subtle and arch, the cumin hot sauce allowed each ingredient of the combo plate to express something else‚Ä¶ something intense and forthright, something‚Ä¶ whatever the opposite of banal is. Even the zesty lemon rice tasted new somehow, its citrus essence playfully manifesting like some sort of multi-armed Hindu deity. Can you tell I was in food nirvana? ::chuckle:: After savoring and swallowing a couple more bites of the meal, I peremptorily slammed shut the to-go plate and hastened back to the truck, demanding of Jason to sell me a whole bottle, quick. (I grabbed one each of the other 2 sauces, as I know these‚Äôll make great Christmas presents for a couple of discerning eaters I know. ::chuckle::) It took cosmic restraint on my part not to grace my Haleakala smoothie with a couple of sauce dots just to see if the drink would also‚Ä¶ evolve. LOL. As I left, I bade Harpreet aloha (Jason had gone off with a shopping cart of what looked like recyclables) and raved to her: ‚Äú‚Ä¶you know what that sauce will be good in? Falafel!‚Äù Which the neighbor truck purveys. That will be for another day. Today, we are Indian. The Lebanese can wait. ;-)

1 ‚Äî Out of that star we are born, and to it we will return. I waited, the bridge under me shuddering with each passing car and I wondered; why no one else was here with me to see the sun light upon the glass, the dusking sky mirrored on the water, the colors changing from one ineffable hue to the next. The mote of a bird, reflected, skims sharply upon the surface of the pond and draws a line, an angle, onto which a tiny amphibian appears, breaking the surface, casting a perfectly circular ripple that grows then vanishes as quickly as it appeared.

2 ‚Äî Out of that star you were born, and to it you will return. The chaos of the time looms: an accidental president, a moral void, not a single compassionate bone in his body‚Ä¶ barks lies and tweets hatreds so routinely and so heedlessly that you begin to question your sanity. But it also recedes: there is nothing about cruel reality that cannot be cured by a simple pond by the sea at the close of a day. Wiser souls and more wizened hearts have seen worse, you are sure; hence know the secrets that exist. It is all a mirror, and you look, so as to see.

3 ‚Äî Out of that star I was born, and to it I will return. I could hear the little childrens‚Äô voices, running with and then after their mom and dad, all eager to reach the beach before the sun dipped under the horizon. Everyone else was there, and it was all I could do to not yell across the pond to say: come here! This view is great, too! ::chuckle:: I thought to find that mother later, as it was she who I captured standing there, immolated, consumed‚Äîfixed‚Äîby that transfixing, setting, sun: ‚ÄúAloha, I have a gift for you, if you please‚Ä¶‚Äù

On the first morning of the new year, visited the Maui Jinsha Shinto shrine in Paukukalo, which I'd never seen in all my years here. The current caretaker of the temple told me the story of that extraordinary wood painting: "The Thousand Horses" was painted in 1912. Each of the horses represented an individual who had donated $1 for the construction of the temple. The person's name is written on each horse's saddle. $1 at that time was a huge sum, a princely fortune for the Issei sugarcane field workers who lived in the plantation camps. The paint on much of the surface of the wood is fading, chipped away by time and weather.

Sometimes dusk is a paragon of indifference‚Äîthings will shade to darkness and oblivion whether we like it or not, and no amount of seeing will stop the loss of light, shape, form, color, texture, thing-ness. But then. The moment we give in to that entropy‚Ä¶ all of a sudden dusk becomes immanent: it is the be-all and end-all of your day. Of your days. And, as such, the fact of its vanishing draws the circle closed. The sense of the day retards to the dark, like the dying echo of a piano sonata‚Äôs last notes, and you remember the point of your breath once again. Again.

Night is the coefficient of loss. It‚Äôs always in that lee time of day that I remember them. It stands to reason. The noonday glare demands your attention, whether you like it or not, and you are lost in the thickets of consciousness (what that is: will be one of the last mysteries our kind will ever come to understand). But nighttime arrives and, with it, the ghosts. Your ghosts. Mine. This evening, it was someone‚Äôs beloved dog. Her name was Quinny. She stayed lit in Esther‚Äôs life for just a little while, and then left. But for her memories, now graven in dreaming. Tomorrow evening it will be someone else. I will outwait the noonday demon, and find the shades again.

Am drawn to these forms like the proverbial moth to flame: a glassy liquid surface, no breeze to ruffle its face, elements that play with the light: clouds, a gradient sky, landshapes that carve the frame into quadrants, thirds, wholes.

This one is up at elevation somewhere. Somewhere rather unlikely. But when time and weather and happenstance interface just so‚Ä¶ the plane of things, the look of the eye, the capturing of it all, becomes an act of sheer magic. At least to me, it does. I never tire of it.

Finding it is only a fraction of the result, luck is largely the thing that holds it together, skill an artifact of age and time. Still, one does have to have the kind of imagination that is in plentiful supply in a child‚Äôs mind and in her eye. Bereft of that, the world is a banal place, an entity to just live in, not to expand through.

This evening, as the sun set, was a good example. I shall hold the story to myself, as the caretaker of the place, a Filipino woman short in stature as my mother, bade me keep the secret and, in her sudden telling allowed me temporary mastery of the pond‚Äôs verge, the animal-trodden path, the padlocked gate, opened.

interiority, part 2

It is difficult to reconcile such tempered beauty with the chaos that is to come. There will be the empty spaces where some of us will seek our last refuge but even those, I expect, will be tainted by our hands, our intemperate stewardship of all that was good. Our only home.

It‚Äôs not easy to gauge the depth and texture of things when they‚Äôre in such stark contrast, like this. That ragged curve there is a massive volcano, on whose flanks lie the dreams of some, the histories of many. And if I didn‚Äôt tell you, you‚Äôd miss this: Venus and Jupiter in the upper right quadrant, bare pixels of light. On that scale, of our solar system, imagination should be constructed.

In the foreground the glassy pond, on whose surface the gradient of early sky recapitulates. As I entered the gate to this preserve, two nene geese accosted me, interrogatively. One, likely the male, distended its wings, stepped to me, uttering a baleful hiss. By the feet of the other, a single gosling. I nodded an apology, walked softly away.

It is impossible to reconcile such fleeting contact with the imperturbable wildness of it all. At the edge of the water, I crouched, framing things with one amateur eye, penetrating it with the cynical other. Looked back to where the creatures had been, and saw, through to the dark, nothing‚Äînot motion, not shape, no evidence of the chaos to come.

soon, only the unseen

Dusk beguiles, as always. Don‚Äôt do it, she pleaded‚Ä¶ don‚Äôt cross that road before our flimsy barriers go up. It was as if we could hear them in the dark, their instincts pulling them from the sea to the pond inshore, but before that, this highway.

Once upon a time, my mother and I joined with a group of devoted honu protectors; naturalists, all, even though we came from different walks of life. It would be before dawn, or even shortly after midnight. We‚Äôd stand with kerosene lamps or flashlights, cordoning off North Kihei Road as it passes along Ma‚Äôalaea Beach, asking motorists kindly to wait‚Äîor take the longer route home‚Äîso as to not disturb the migration of egg-laying turtles.

It worked for a while, for a few years. And then, the human outcry overweening, a fence was erected instead, to prevent the turtles from their slow crawl inland. For now, it is to be this way and this way only and always, as long as we walk on our two legs and lead with our brains. Who are they, anyway, these inferior species, to dictate what we should or should not do?

But nature has a way of reclaiming itself, in its own time. Before long, the ocean will rise and cover this road, which will melt under the eonic onslaught of waves, wind, water. Sand will accrue, here as elsewhere and, should they endure our stifling presence, the honu will return, to cross once again from death to life. Theirs‚Ä¶ ‚Ä¶and where echo no words‚Äînot ours, no dross of speech, no forking slipperiness of human tongues.

In order to catch a fleeting silver spectrum, patience. To fit the eyescape to the actual scene, years of fiddling with quanta. To render a story to the plane of the seen, imagination.

Thank goodness the phone alarm woke me up, as the dream was about to turn into a nightmare. But as I stood over the bathroom sink, blearily washing sleep from my eyes, I remembered that, years ago, I‚Äôd hit on the right method to transform the onset of a nightmare into lucid dreaming. Flying was involved, usually. In the segment of dream just before the story could turn into horror, I was gliding down a huge wave, on a boogie board, all the way to the shore. It never broke. 
Likewise, I see this sky now, and am able to capture it in a series of dreamlike moments; my hands and feet moving my body from one subtle place to the next, angling myself just so‚Ä¶ so as to capture the folds and phrases of the early morning, unspooling itself before me like wordless dreaming.
The sun broke through, a little while ago...

Until they could sit together at some nameless table at an undesignated time, at random, sharing a thoughtfully-crafted ale, there would be a lapse of knowing.

He is going about his life, in serene innocence; I would not have it any other way. (There will be time aplenty to ponder, perhaps to grieve; and, of course, to find again and somehow the joy in what once was.) Once upon a time, my father found himself thrust on the precipice-edge of a mortal dilemma: to deny what he saw with his very own eyes, lest he never see his family again. He chose, painfully‚Ä¶ but, in the hindsight of decades later, wisely. He would see things like the mirror image of cloud and sky on the surface of a blissed-out pond perched rather unlikely upon the shoulders of a hill, just like this. He thought he never would. But it came with a price.

He does not know, nor will he ever, what it took for me to find him. There was a kind of death involved, in the way that oppressed peoples find themselves living in the dreadful day-to-day. I see that kind of dispensation threatening now, in the sordid risk of this American presidency. I do have hope that his base and banal instincts will still be dashed on the shoals of the law.

It was something else my father faced, in a culture and history far away‚Ä¶ but o lord is it dreadfully, frighteningly, familiar. I sit here, wishing a gentle unremarkable future on my own son but I feel that time has come, and gone. So, a state of innocence, now, is good. That I once held when dad faced that mirroring abyss.

Away from the tempest of time, this. Crouching, I wait on the intersection of sun setting behind me and the wind-stilled pond, the painted clouds, a risen moon generous in its way.

Innocent of the claims on my consciousness, that singular satellite takes the light and hurls it straight at me, my vision halved: seeing, and nothingness. Two sides of the same face.

There are things to contemplate, but also  dread to allay. Mortality a serpent coiled ‚Äòround my neck, biding its time, jealous of nothing and no one. It is the moon, on whom I wait, watch, see.

At this early Saturday hour no one here walks yet, leaving me alone with memory. I bend down to peer at the glassy sand, willing the occlusion of years away, in an effort to recover the sound of her voice, the gentle fall of her footsteps on the incipient day. It wasn't so long ago, yesterday being but a fragment of a figment of time and the very essence of maya. So I do remember her smile, as if it had been given but a moment ago, and the dark yields to an easy exhalation of breath, a simple incantation: here, now, be.

1 ‚Ä¢ ma‚Äôalaea
...the blue: from sky above, the ocean below, arrowed sheet of horizon coming straight to my eyes, and from the inside: once upon a time in early childhood there was a sound akin to something so intimate it reminded me of nothing less than the hiss and plash of the world outside the womb: we were on a narrow road, in a jeepney, on an island, approaching the sea for my first time and it was waves: the sound of waves on a beach, white noise of the universe: sea, wind, water, sand and i am brought reverentially back to that moment from here where i stand: on this beach, ma‚Äôalaea, the interpenetration of color and memory forcing me away from the thingness of body, the passage of time, the sensation of place, the essence of blue.

2 ‚Ä¢ maui
‚Ä¶that dream the other night: in it i had told her it was nothing like i‚Äôd ever felt before, as i held her close, then i told him it was a secret i‚Äôd never divulged to anyone but now was doing it to him, for them, as i held him closer: then shortly, when we moved to form the circle and to hold hands before yielding forward: a child interposed himself, asking me to hold him, and then suddenly the whole world felt right in a way it had never been before: it was us, maui, in that moment of longing and sadness and love and loss and all became clear and understood: prayerfully, manifestly, one: without the physicality of being but with the most complete knowing that had ever possessed me, in waking or in dream.

3 ‚Ä¢ hawai‚Äôi
‚Ä¶this place: when we arrived here, near to 40 years ago, it did feel like coming home, finally and with a sense of rightness that defied any logic: not that of history, of  resistance, of escape, of revolution: here, at last, we had come to a place of refuge, like so many had done before us in search of a different life but hoping for the same manifestations of cloth, plant, music, love: taken in hand by the vagaries and nuances of life in a different archipelago, the alien words nevertheless strung with familiar sounds, syllables, sensations: these were islands atop an invisible but manifestly powerful spot on the surface of the planet that defined just one thing, hawaii‚Äôi: our longed-for, beloved, eternal, place.

4 ‚Ä¢ honua
...the earthen and elemental beauty of all this is such that there is a ringing in me right now: something is vibrating to the awe-ful spirit of things and has found me at long last it has found me: that it speaks of a deepening existential crisis to our kind, ensconced both subtly and permanently to the outer skin of our home planet is something that by rights should paralyze: but instead it galvanizes, in the sound of these crashing waves a reminder that the notions of the children, unencumbered by the hoary leather of cynical adulthood, are to be welcomed: as the possessors of hope that they are, poised as we all are between the infinite catalepsis of nothingness and the familiar, old, young, thingness of this earth.

This evening at the piko of the UH Maui campus, about a hundred or so of us were taught a powerful hula that was instrumental in the stopping of the construction of the Thirty-Meter Telescope back in April of 2015. That may sound, to the unsuspecting ear, like a thoroughly ridiculous thing to say; but that observation is backed by the simple, impermeable solidity of historical fact: the last line before the construction crews could proceed up to the summit of Mauna Kea was‚Ä¶ a line of kia‚Äôi, k≈´puna, kanaka, dancing this hula with steadfast resolve and the immobility of mauna. Lanakila‚Äôs 65-year old mother had the bruises to show for it on her body‚Äîso fiercely did she do this hula‚Äîwhich she texted to him‚Ä¶ while he was at the Temple of the Oracle in Delphi. Yeah, that one, in Greece. ::chuckle:: So Lanakila taught us all the hula ‚ÄúO hanau ka mauna o Kea,‚Äù a mele hanau (birth chant) for Kauikeaouli, Kamehameha III. It is a description of Mauna Kea in a genealogical context. Among many other things, this young kia‚Äôi and kumu hula is a brilliant teacher, and within an hour had taught us, the assembled kanaka and hoaloha, an extraordinary thing indeed. We will carry this wherever we now go, won‚Äôt we‚Ä¶ Torie, Kevin, Teri?

Where‚Äôve the years gone, my bonny young son‚Ä¶ a line from a song half-remembered. 22 yours, 17 of those ours shared. It‚Äôs been a dreamlike journey of family‚Äîmaking one where none existed, or was expected. It‚Äôs true what is said about love: that it is loss and discovery, empathy and bafflement, silence and voice‚Ä¶ and a thousand and twenty-two other things all wrapped up in one embrace that no polemic can sunder. We walk under the lights of this legendary road, the streams of bodies, traffic, commerce and it‚Äôs like it always was: together, companionable silence, amusing observations, words half-rendered as we know what the other is thinking. So then I am growing old, and you just starting out, but I do remember the thrill, the fear, the substance of it all. With every breath left to me, then, I wish you: life, love, joy.

At a little past 1 on this Saturday afternoon the sea west of Keawala‚Äôi is a metallic shade of turquoise, its surface perturbed by advance elements of Hurricane Hector (Cat. 3) somewhere southeast of the islands, churning this way with strengthening, easy malevolence. (Last night I called Pono on O‚Äôahu to suggest that he and his cousins spend part of the weekend stocking up on water and other supplies, in the event Hector escalates to a 4 or even 5 by the time it appears in our ambit sometime early next week.) The view from here, glimpsed from this low lavarock parapet, asserts that the ocean is innocent‚Äîfor now; but that it could emerge from its quiet‚Ä¶ entirely heedless of our animal angsts and, as it has always done, manifest its sway over all our affairs, without time, and beyond it. Past this vista, then, a disquieting, still-invisible, storm. There is much to be disturbed about the prevailing human predicament‚ÄîI suppose this is as it always has been. But the fraying climate worries me the most, as it speaks in gestures far beyond any of our collective will to prevent, mitigate.

I will be dead long before the worst of the consequences of our failed stewardship of this planet but this gives me no keening solace: for, after all, our children will still be here and then, theirs.

Mid-morning, Saturday, August 11 ‚Äî primary election day in Hawaii nei (although many have already voted early, in the days and weeks prior). Very low tide, at half past 10. The view of the ocean here never fails to stop me in my tracks. Right this moment, the dappled quality of turquoise and bluegreen arrests. I feel in this scene a dangerous* scrim in the existential play of climate change; it is a drama playing itself out all over the planet right now, and the analyses and prognoses by those in the know is grim. (*I say it is ‚Äòdangerous‚Äô because the lambent quality of it can easily lull one into thinking nothing is amiss‚Äîbut something is most definitely so.)
This lustrous, silverine sky above Makena at the moment ‚Äî 3:37 p.m., Saturday the 18th ‚Äî hinting of another hurricane approaching from the southeast...

That kid in the ball cap is on a college campus today taking a test and it scares the living daylights out of me. It's not the test or results that I fear -- he'll do great and the results don't matter to me. What scares me is the fact that in a very short time, he'll be doing this all on his own. No parachute, no dad sitting in the hallway for three hours to give him a hug when he's done. He'll figure out where the business office is to write a check, he'll sign all of the paperwork himself, he'll remember on his own to use the restroom beforehand; and I just hope that when he's done, he'll at least give me a call and look for a virtual hug. Moments like this make me realize I need that hug just as much as he does... go get 'em Cohen, I know you've got this but it sure is hard watching it happen so fast!
#prouddad #dirtinmyeyes

For the last 6 months we've been renovating a historic home in downtown Grapevine, TX. It is not for the faint of heart. 
We were finally able to move in last week and are going through the slow process of getting things like mirrors, curtains, and towel racks hung. 
I didn't do a great job of posting pictures throughout but will try and catch up with a few after the fact. 
This great room used to be 4 separate rooms with a pantry and water heater closet right in the middle. Most of the floors throughout the house are original 2" red oak from 1954 which we sanded and refinished with an almost clear stain that just had a small amount of white mixed in. They turned out fantastic. 
The kitchen is completely brand new with an 8' island added in for good measure. 
What you don't see here is that the window next to the kitchen is soon to be replaced with another door and steps down to the back patio and pool area.

#grapevinetx #midcenturymodern #historichome

Yes, this is a picture of a bathroom and yes, I'm kind of fond of the floor. I wanted to put some fancy type in the floor with, "wash your hands" or "you look nice today" but the decision maker in the house wasn't having any of it.
.
Prior to the remodel, this bathroom didn't exist. There was a third toilet in the house but it was oddly located in the laundry room. One can only assume that folding laundry while using the facilities is a little known, proper time-management technique. Noted.
.
For this one we did a matte finish 1" hexagon tile in black and white. You might notice a couple pieces of tape on the floor though where we're going to change out the colors due to our OCD-ness and the pattern being a little off.
.
Come and visit and I'll let you use this little gem of a half-bath; I won't even charge you for it.

Lester was a shy man. He had secrets. #inktober
I was inspired by how my back feels. #inktober
‚ÄúWhat the?!‚Äù He slammed on the brakes. He looked deep into the eyes of what halted him and felt that it had something to say of grave importance. #inktober
He was warned about the giant. He was warned too late. #inktober
It was too late to run. #inktober
The earth shattered beneath the giant‚Äôs feet. #inktober
The city teemed with it‚Äôs citizens clogging the streets. No one knew what to do. How do you deal with a giant skeleton? #inktober
A fierce wind swept through the valley over the hills. Lester knew what he had to do. #inktober
Like a flash, Lester was gone. Then a mysterious figure approached. It was El Fastamador! #inktober
El Fantasmador shouted. A rumble from the heavens returned through beams of light a sword. It gracefully made its way to El Fantasmador‚Äôs hands. #inktober
El Fantasmador gazed into his sword and stated, ‚ÄúI will vanquish this filthy beast.‚Äù #inktober
The giant stomped it‚Äôs foot with great force creating a huge cloud of dust. #inktober
A sound from deep bellow of sadness and discordance roared. Fantasmas from the beyond rose through fissures the giants foot created. #inktober
With a furious drive, El Fantasmador worked his way toward the giant skeleton. #inktober
All that was left, was a trail of bodies dispatched from their wretched existence. #inktober
The giant was blinded. It was time to strike. #inktober
The giant shouted louder than a foghorn. Was it pain? #inktober
El Fantasmador didn‚Äôt have time to care about the shout. His shoes squeaked as he jumped toward the giant skeleton. #inktober
El Fantasmador climbed the giant skeleton‚Äôs ribcage, stabbing it on the way up. Skeleton jelly began to ooze from the giants bones. #inktober
The loss of jelly made the skeleton weak. The giant skeleton lost its balance and fell with a thunderous clap. #inktober
Thinking about these two all day and how much they meant to me.
After the dust had settled, El Fantasmador was reunited with his sword. #inktober
El Fantasmador put away his sword and found that he left nothing but destruction #inktober
He did the only thing he knew was right. He placed on his cleaning mask and got to work. #inktober

Sometimes I‚Äôm very lucky and see some incredible birds while sitting in my backyard. Recently I was lucky enough to have these two beauties fly over me and land on a nearby telephone pole. The sounds of their wings cutting through the air is magnificent. 

One thing that was interesting was how quiet it was while they perched on that pole. I definitely wouldn‚Äôt want them to see me if I was a lil bird.

First week of using a single monitor and it‚Äôs been quite a positive experience! For a start, it‚Äôs appeased the minimalist and focused approach I wanted on my physical desk; there‚Äôs more space and less in it making it feel more focused. On the desktop I‚Äôve enjoyed it, but I do miss a second screen at least sometimes. At work I leave my MacBook open but only have my bullet journal in view. I was making some patch updates to a personal project last night and felt I should have that extra screen there, but after some time I realised I was getting the things I wanted done quickly. See, without another screen you have to be focused on what you are doing; if you do have two different things on one screen, then it needs to be high value to take up precious pixels.

New year and a new office setup! Experimenting with a single display I realised the issues I had working on multiple displays I had. I also found out what the limitations of one display to avoid. Decided to go with two 4K displays running at native resolution! Both LG27UK600 (because an extra ¬£250 for USB-C option didn't see worth it) mounted on a dual monitor arm. So far, having used this for about 2 weeks on/off, it's been the best. Lots more pixels to output on, less physical space. Having it as two displays (rather than a single ultra-wide or super ultra-wide) means splitting work in a way that reflects my workflow. Few things to change still as well as some ‚Äúout of shot‚Äù features I added that I may talk about in the future. But yeah, enjoying my new home office setup!

Good Monday coding fans!

Working on a internal CLI tool to help with some workflows; hopefully cut time down from 5-15 minutes of work to... one command. Writing a CLI I‚Äôm finding myself massively reliant on tests to check each part of the process, though some are going to be tricky to check without manual intervention. It‚Äôs the nature of this little beast.

The CLI is being written in TypeScript. I know some folks will say ‚Äúwhy not python‚Äù or "why not bash"? Well sometimes using the best technical tool for the job is not the most apt tool for the environment. Due to a number of business and technical choices around this, a JS/TypeScript solution works perfectly. The barrier to entry for this CLI is super low and doesn't require much setup (install node, install package). The idea is for folks to run 'n go, and this tech stack does it perfectly. If it was a previous job then it would of been PHP, but I'm not using that tech stack no longer so it's a no-go. 

How was your Monday?

Whisky Wednesday

Naturally, if you're short on your Amazon Prime Now order, it only seems right to  buy a bottle of something and this little whisky found it's way into my basket. An odd choice of cart filler at 9 the morning, but what can I say...

Really, what?

Aberlour 10 year old single malt is one of those whiskies you won't mistaken for scotch. In a good way this has some of the characteristic of that typical Scotch whisky; the sweet woody caramel flavours and a hint of pear that has a spice that lingers after you finish. I've heard folks refer to this sort of whisky as a "breakfast whisky" (maybe that's why I ordered it at 9am); it's a taste you can sip on all day and enjoy whilst not getting too involved in it's flavours. It's a good whisky to keep in!

Let‚Äôs talk COVID-19 and diabetes. See, diabetic‚Äôs are in the extremely clinically vulnerable shielding group, but we‚Äôre still heightened as a clinical group. There have been a higher number of deaths of those with diabetes over the age of 40 than without - our ‚ÄúCOVID age‚Äù is somewhat increased. This is due to how our bodies cope when we get unwell as we‚Äôll find ourselves insulin resistant, meaning that we‚Äôll need to tighten control of blood sugars and possible increase the amount of insulin we‚Äôll need to do. Whilst blood sugars are high, we are more prone to complications and this starts a extremely up-hill battle. We have specialist ‚Äúsick day rules‚Äù to follow that help control blood sugars and get us on the mend, but as COVID-19 is still new and not much is known, it‚Äôs advice is the best we can go on without knowing much else. A number of diabetes groups are heavily researching the effects of the virus on diabetics to help reduce the risks and provide the best advice they can offer, it‚Äôs still best advice to stay away and keep wearing the mask. If I‚Äôm honest, I like wearing a mask, got an outlaw feel to it!

Eyes are another point of issue with diabetics. Again with the blood vessels and high blood sugars, the eye can become easily damaged with most diabetics over 10 years developing some form of retinopathy. It‚Äôs where the blood vessels start to break down and bleed out. I have background retinopathy, but this is to be expected and is nothing to worry about. If I leave my eyes unchecked or ignore high blood sugars over a period of time, my eye sight can start to be affected and eventually blindness. Last year I amassed a collection of whisky samples that I've never got round to trying. As a regular Wednesday treat I'm going to try sample these and give my impressions. I'm by no means an experienced whisky drinker, but I do enjoy a good dram, so please don't hate me if I go way off course with some of these!

The first is a mystery whisky given to me by @whiskyswimmer of @wessexwhiskyclub. No idea at all what this is other than it's a whisky... or is it a whiskey? Starting with the nose, it gives off that fruit cake, which I love, with slight ethanol, making me think this is a strong one, though maybe not cask strength. From the taste, I'm going to say this is from a sherry cask, probably Oloroso over PX, with that dry sweetness of currents and nuts with a slight marzipan/almond edge to it. Not sure if it's a blended whisky (guessing no), but I get hints of bourbon as well, making me think it sat in one of those casks for a period. The finish is dry and long, which now makes me think this is a cask strength!

It's a whisky I would defiantly buy. It's that falvour profile I like and that experience of a good after-dinner whisky, but not an all-nighter. I like a whisky that you can pour a dram, sip, enjoy and put away for another night. Now to find out what it is... @whiskyswimmer?

That time of the week where I pick a dram and tell you what I think and probably do an awful job explaining flavours... It's Whisky Wednesday!

Today's dram from @drinksbythedram is a Deanston 14-Year-Old Organic Single Malt, 46.3% ABV. Not knowingly tried an organic so that's something different here, but it's a highland whisky, which is normally an easy drinker, nothing offensive, but enough to let you know you're drinking a whisky.

On the nose with this one, it took me a while but it initially had a somewhat earthy aroma but didn't seem right. A few more sniffs it struck me as a mix of fresh cooking apples and sweet malt. The taste clears it brings out that sweet baking flavours of pears and muscovado; a very warming sensation. I often say that this sort fo profile in a whisky is after dinner one, a desert whisky, but that doesn't fit here. An autumn whisky for sure with the finish having a medium length spice to it. I think this is one for a fireworks night or Halloween; a whisky to watch the leaves change colour. A nice understated whisky that wouldn‚Äôt go amiss in a collection.

‚Äî‚Äî

Wow, a busy week so far, hence no uploads as of yet. But tonight is Whisky Wednesday and so I must face that horrible task of opening a dram of something and sampling its liquid insides.

Tonight is my last dram of @drinksbythedram's Xmas collection and it's @theglenallachie_ 15-Year-Old Single Malt at 46% ABV.

Now, the nose I immediately get that distinct raisin smell with that caramel or butterscotch hint and possibly apple or pears right at the end there. The colour of this whisky might be skewing my views as, well... look at how deep that oaky brown is! Almost the same shade as my table. The taste is very interesting, nothing I was expecting; it's almost bitter like dark chocolate, or even akin to a chocolate sauce you'll pour over venison. But the raisin flavours are super strong in this one, reminds me of the red box raisins eating them as a kid. There are spices flowing in there around the woody notes. The finish is short with this one with more of the aromas staying around rather than the flavours itself.

This is an odd mix, in a good way, of an all-nighter but also a savour whisky. Probably more of the all-nighter one as I could easily be drinking this one around friends having a gas. It makes me want to try more of the GlenAllachie range now as it's a very distinct "scotch" that I'd love to keep in for folks to try.

It's Wednesday and I have a whisky. As is the tradition I shall obnoxiously taste it and provide my level headed feedback that is more akin to somebody who is drunk and is trying to sound like they know what the hell they are talking about.

Today is a dram of Bunnahabhain 12-year-old single malt (46.3% ABV) from @summertonclub ! They sent out their bi-monthly bottle this week (which is rather nice I must say) and provided this sample with it. I've tried a few rarer Bunnahabhains plus their Sti√πireadair (which I've posted about previously) and their range is quite complex. Whilst not massively into their Sti√πireadair, I've heard great things about this whisky.

Normally with a whisky from Islay, you are expecting peat but @bunnahabhain doesn't typically follow suit, which is no different here. The nose immediately brings up spiced sun-dried fruits with a sweeter floral sense towards the end there; reminds me of a strong (alcohol) wine at the end. The taste is rich with nuts and fruit, trail mix wise with that almonds, apple, cashews and citrus peel with a little toffee in there somewhere. That finish is quick but fragrant with a little dryness to it, almost coats the mouth. No peat in this for me or even smoke, so if you aren't into that then you are very safe with this bottle.

I can see why Summerton sent this sample with their main bottle. I like it! I've been looking at buying this for a while now but wasn't sure and ended up getting something else, but I think I'll need to have one of these in as a keeper. It's got a lot going for it at a reasonable price tag (around ¬£40 for a 70cl). Well worth a try!

Hi, I‚Äôm Neil and I‚Äôm a type 1 diabetic. I stab myself with insulin and draw blood. Those who followed me last year may remember I did a month of photos relating to my diabetes. I‚Äôm doing it again this month and hope to teach even more to people about diabetes. Though I‚Äôll mostly cover type 1 diabetes, I hope to give facts about type 2 as well. I‚Äôm also aiming to squash misconceptions and myths about this condition that many have. But, if you have any questions I‚Äôll answer them no matter how personal; no holds bar. #type1 #type1diabetic #type1diabetes #t1d #diabetic #diabetes #bluenovember #diabetesawareness #diabetesawarenessmonth #bluenovemberüíô

For years, as a kid, I never knew that the bottom drawer of a fridge was a salad crisper. It‚Äôs always been where I‚Äôve kept my insulin. The same goes for the butter shelf in the fridge, that‚Äôs where I keep my current insulin. Even the fridge at work, the butter shelf houses my insulin! #type1 #type1diabetic #type1diabetes #t1d #diabetic #diabetes #bluenovember #diabetesawareness #diabetesawarenessmonth #bluenovemberüíô

Here‚Äôs what I stab myself with four times a day. It‚Äôs weird to think that the little droplet, the insulin, is what keeps me alive. Also, this is the only way I can get my body to process it is via a needle. It‚Äôs not as bad as it seems, there‚Äôs worse needles and this isn‚Äôt the painful part of diabetes; there‚Äôs two parts that actually are. But this little synthetic hormone, this is my very life line. #type1 #type1diabetic #type1diabetes #t1d #diabetic #diabetes #bluenovember #diabetesawareness #diabetesawarenessmonth #bluenovemberüíô #insulin #needle

This is a typical Saturday night drink for me, a glass of whiskey. Not normally this much but I‚Äôm getting rid of a bottle! Any way, I like a drink and this is fine for my diabetes, the main thing I need to be aware of is alcohol can lower blood sugars. This can be a bit of a concern when going out for a session as I need to weigh up the sugar content of a drink against the alcohol. What works for me is high alcohol as most of the sugar is gone, so all I need to is top up on carbs. What has happened due to this also is my tolerance is rather high, so if I‚Äôm acting a bit ‚Äúdrunk‚Äù the more logical issue is I‚Äôm low. It‚Äôs a way of enjoying yourself and feeling the nicer affects of alcohol without the worries of high blood sugars or confusion of drunk or low. I‚Äôm not a fan of getting drunk either way, I drink for flavour hence my enjoyment of rather expensive whiskies! #type1 #type1diabetic #type1diabetes #t1d #diabetic #diabetes #bluenovember #diabetesawareness #diabetesawarenessmonth #bluenovemberüíô #alcohol #whiskey #whisky #whiskygeek

Also, this was a bloody difficult photo to take as my hands were shaking so much! #type1 #type1diabetic #type1diabetes #t1d #diabetic #diabetes #bluenovember #diabetesawareness #diabetesawarenessmonth #bluenovemberüíô

One of the biggest issues I have with diabetes is not the blood tests or injections or the really crap feelings I have. Nope, it‚Äôs the fact that I‚Äôm limited in what I can drink. The amount of soft drinks with sugars/carbs in them is the worst. Even if they say sugar free or ‚Äúzero‚Äù sugar, they could have carbs; more often than not nowadays. You may see me drink mainly Pepsi Max as that‚Äôs what I know is safe and the only thing that tastes good for me. Fruit juices, flavoured waters and also health drinks are shockingly bad for me. Weirdly, this is mainly an issue in the UK; in places like Ireland and Canada, I can often pick a whole range of drinks to have with a true 0.0 carb content. Seems like a minor thing, and it is, but when your out and want a quick drink of something other than water, you‚Äôre massively limited. If the UK truly wants to stop kids drinking sugary drinks, then maybe do more to incentivise getting true sugar free drinks in the market. Last thing; a lot of what you read about artificial sweeteners is bull. #type1 #type1diabetic #type1diabetes #t1d #diabetic #diabetes #bluenovember #diabetesawareness #diabetesawarenessmonth #bluenovemberüíô

I love lazing at home playing video games. I‚Äôm somewhat healthy, I try and go to the gym when I can and I eat fairly healthy (not ‚Äúdiet‚Äù healthy, which 90% of it is bull). Some may see my video game lifestyle as s possible reason why I‚Äôm diabetic. Many people think diabetes is directly related to being overweight; this is not true for type 1 or type 2. Closest thing true to that is being overweight may increase likelihood of type 2 diabetes, but it‚Äôs not a deciding factor. In fact most people with type 2 aren‚Äôt overweight and most overweight don‚Äôt develop it (I think that‚Äôs source from Diabetes UK, but I can fact check if anybody queries that). With regards to my diabetes, type 1, it‚Äôs most likely caused by genetics and unknown factors. Anybody can develop it at any time but type 1 is most likely to occur at development stages in life. So, if somebody has diabetes, you‚Äôll be mostly wrong to assume it‚Äôs their lifestyle. Actually, I found out recently there‚Äôs a whole host of body building groups that are made up of type 1 and 2 diabetics, so healthy people can be diabetic! #type1 #type1diabetic #type1diabetes #t1d #diabetic #diabetes #bluenovember #diabetesawareness #diabetesawarenessmonth #bluenovemberüíô

I‚Äôve always struggled to explain what high blood sugars actually feels like. There‚Äôs different levels to it. At first you just feel heavy, under your skin. You then get that feeling of lactic acid, but more like of you were to tense your muscles really hard, edging to the point of causing a cramp, but constant. Then comes the sharp headaches, when you‚Äôre really high, they almost paralyse you. I‚Äôve been taken to the floor before in sheer pain I thought I was having a brain aneurism, but it was moving all over, under my skin. My pain levels are very high, but the times that‚Äôs happened, it‚Äôs horrific. #type1 #type1diabetic #type1diabetes #t1d #diabetic #diabetes #bluenovember #diabetesawareness #diabetesawarenessmonth #bluenovemberüíô

This body. 
It has fought hard: on the field, the court, in the gym, in the world.

Broken and fractured bones, stretched ligaments, scars.

This body. Two pregnancies. Holding another human, and letting it go out into the world.

These arms. They‚Äôve held babies, held friends in both sorrow and celebration, held love and let love go.

These legs have run races both literal and figurative. They‚Äôve stood strong and they‚Äôve crumbled.

This body. It is mine. It is the only one I have. I am proud of this body. Finally. I refuse to treat it poorly, to say or think words that do not serve it fully. Improvement is important. It is possible. But so is love; for our bodies, for ourselves. 
So bear it all ‚Äì let your body take up all the space it needs. And only surround yourself with others who feel the same.
