This morning was my first day teaching at the Levine JCC. It just now occurred to me that the morning of 9/11/01 I was in ceramics class at UCF as a student. And here I was 16 years later, in a studio again but now as instructor. Weird how timing works out.
.
In the meantime, it was kinda awesome to wake up and "go to work" knowing that clay was waiting for me. Most other classes I've taught have been at night, as has been my own time to make work. I think I could get used to this. Goodbye computer and desk, hello clay and wheel!

Took about an hour into this test fire to find out that it would fail. Luckily I was sitting next to the kiln working and heard the cup explode and stopped the firing before the other pieces got ruined too. I shouldn't be surprised. I stupidly put a not quite dry piece in extreme temperatures. I'll use this as a teaching moment for the boys tomorrow and be able to show them how destructive steam and gasses can be! #experimentanddiscover #ohwell #explodedkiln #potteriastudio #testfire #clay

Today was a day where the clay made me work for it. Some days you‚Äôre just ‚Äúoff‚Äù and that‚Äôs okay. I haven‚Äôt thrown since early December and there‚Äôs been a lot of loss and stress in our lives since then. Today was my day to finally scratch an itch. To get back on the wheel. To feel like me again. A less empty me. These stupid pots should never have been. I should have quit not long after wrestling to center the first ball. I tell my students ‚ÄúIf you aren‚Äôt centered, then your clay won‚Äôt be.‚Äù Potting is as much a state of mind as it is technical skill. My mind wasn‚Äôt here. Yet, each one of these pots shows an imperfection that flowed out from my center today, and maybe that‚Äôs exactly what I needed. The crud had to come out. And as it did, I wrestled it and cursed it and lo and behold, something was formed from all of that. I guess sometimes we do need a good fight with ourselves. #throwingmylifeaway

So.. the @penlandschool Workshop I am teaching filled on the first day.  But... I am teaching a very different one at my pottery in Wisconsin this summer and I just opened registration today.  Limited to 7 participants, 6 places left.

June 30-July 13.

This is one of my favorite images from the workshop I taught at my pottery in Gresham last summer.  The workshop is called the Intimate Anagama. 
In the image @paulstokstad sits alone with the hot kiln, pouring over the kiln log.  His intensity is matched by the fire beside him.  His involvement is complete and we see him in this intimate moment.

The workshop is designed to create this kind of intense learning experience.  There is community work, there is alone time, there is equal part in decision making, there are demos, a guest artist, community meals and you leave with 12 cubic feet of your own work fired by you.

If you are trying to get a grasp of wood firing, this workshop is for you.

See more details on my website in my profile, or message me.

This is what the bottom of a mug looks like when it‚Äôs in the middle of being trimmed.  Excess clay is shaved away to do several things: balance the weight of the mug, reveal a level foot ring for the cup to sit on and a place for the glaze to stop, and generally enhance the profile of the mug as a whole. While this task is somewhat hypnotic and relaxing, I‚Äôd much rather improve my throwing so that I can skip this step all together. (And not have a ‚Äúfat-bottomed mug.) I love the process but at a certain point, if you want to make any money at this craft, you have to find ways to make your production more efficient. Goals.

Another piece from a recent #rakufiring. Coincidentally enough, I didn‚Äôt use raku clay. Which I understand can be risky because the that clay body is better suited to handle the thermal shock of plucking the pot out of an 1800 degree fire and throwing it a bucket of combustible material for 10 minutes and then submerging it in cold water to immediately cool it off. A harsh process not made for the faint clay bodies. This was Highwater Clay‚Äôs #littleloafers. A ‚Äúthrow away‚Äù demo pot to show my students how to use a hump mold. It is covered with ONE GLAZE COLOR. (Red Luster) The areas that are green are where it has been oxidized and the shiny coppery red areas on the bottom are evidence of reduction in those spots. I have a little bit of carbon to scrub off it still, but even so, it‚Äôs a super lustrous piece. And no longer a ‚Äúthrow away pot‚Äù üòù

Some get a gold watch, but for MY early retirement, I got this sweet name tag from the great people I worked with for the last 2.5 years. I‚Äôm humbled and honored to be remembered by this name. I already miss being a part of that team but am so thankful they helped me learn that there‚Äôs greater value in HOW you do the work than WHAT you do. As a digital designer, it‚Äôs my job to make things look good and work good on screen, but the minute you put pixels over people your design fails. Putting each other first cultivated a family, a level of respect, an appreciation for diverse thinking, and a commitment to fun. I believe what grew out of that was better work and more successful design than if we had ‚Äústuck to our strengths‚Äù and been ‚Äúhighly driven professionals.‚Äù This was work worth doing. üíô

I see a lot of beautiful art on the Internet. And maybe if I had seen this online first I‚Äôd have a different draw to it...maybe a spoiled one. Nothing beats turning your shoulder to discover you share the same physical space as a piece of art as stunning as this. Do your soul a favor and seek out art in real life. Today's (mis)adventure took us along Shelf Road, which is an historic wagon road to gold mines. This was taken from a wide spot in the road. Otherwise it's pretty much 45 minutes of single lane dirt trail with the downhill side making the shotgun rider (@bcrest) nice and nervous. ‚Äú4wd and high clearance vehicles only‚Äù, so you know we fit right in.

This rad little dude is a year and a half old today. It's wild to think how much he's changed and how much he's changed us in such a short amount of time. 
He makes us laugh and smile and enjoy the little moments every day. Seeing him figure things out on his own and his personality come through is, to put it lightly, insanely gratifying.

Thanks for letting me be your dad, little man!
I went for a morning spin through an area that had burned just a month or two ago. Super lush and barely any remaining brush.

I didn't think sharing life skills would start so early, but this little guy is just a sponge. While he may not be roasting dogs or s'mores in the immediate future, I can already tell his brain is taking notes and picking up on hundreds of little things every day. Like how storing your bib in the back pocket of your jeans gets more style points. And saying "Wooow" to anything remotely cool instantly makes it cooler for everyone. 
I didn't know what to expect as a dad, but it's hella fun right now. Thanks dude!

My best friend since we were 2.5 years old, Joel (@vingerjoel), got married over the weekend just outside of Jackson, Wyoming.

The weekend and all the festivities felt more like a summer camp than a wedding. It was so much fun to see old roommates and friends come together and act like nothing has changed‚Äîexcept for there being kids and more spouses to hang with.

The crew at this wedding was one of a kind. So many adventurers and people full of life. It felt like half of them were either heading to South America or weren't sure where they'd be off to after the wedding. Kindred spirits from the various walks of Joel and Katy's lives, but all connected through them and their contagious joy for life. Needless to say, we had a blast. And the dancing. Oh the dancing. Nary a wallflower was found in the barn that night.

Banksy + Basquiat + Keith Haring
‚Äî
This piece, and another just across the street, is up between the Underground station and the venue for the design leadership conference I‚Äôve been attending this week (more on that later). Pretty damn cool to see this kind of thing in person.

Become a better design leader. That‚Äôs the reason I came to London; to attend a design conference unlike any I‚Äôve been to before. It was, to put it lightly, incredible.
-
Attendees and speakers came from around the world and from organizations huge (GE, IBM, Spotify, etc.) and small (agencies, 5 person startups, etc). No matter the size of their organization or team, most were struggling with similar things, albeit at different scales. Things like: team structure, stakeholder management, do I even know what I‚Äôm doing, taking advantage of design‚Äôs relatively new seat at the table, etc.
-
It was a bit of a kumbaya ‚ÄúWe‚Äôre all figuring out the same shit as we go‚Äù time (which is insanely reassuring), but also a lot of ‚ÄúMBA for Design‚Äù type sessions that I know will help me and my team do more meaningful work (that stuff will take me quite a while to process).
-

London's answer to the Flatiron Building

#oldstreet #london #architecture #archilovers #architecturephotography #lookup #perspective #lookuparchitecture

Today something different from the usual format. That's what I love of London, the mix of old architecture steps away from modern buildings, the City of London is full sights and corners like this one in St Helen's Square. 
The St. Andrew Undershaft church is one of the few rare churches built around the 15th century which has survived both the Great Fire of London in the 17th century and the Blitz bombing during the second World War. The Church has been partially restored after the IRA's bombings in the 90s.

In the background, the skyscraper named The Scalpel and a reflection of the 30 St Mary Axe, commonly known as the Gherkin Tower because apparently Londoners like to nickname buildings by their look and shape ü•í
.

I resisted for a long time but finally picked up a road bike. 

Once the COVID shutdown started I‚Äôve been doing longer rides to make up for my lost bike commutes. I also began riding more on roads due to the trails being overcrowded. That led to looking for something that was more comfortable on lengthier outings and easier on the climbs up the hills of Arlington. 

By the time I landed on a bike I wanted there were only two left in the country in my size due to everybody buying bikes this summer. I contacted a shop in Ohio that was willing to ship the bike to my local bike store and even cover the shipping and assembly costs!

Still going to keep the trusty hybrid around for riding with the kids and commuting once I go back in to the office (next year? ü§ûüèª).

#newbikeday #roubaix #lycra #cycling #biking #specializedroubaix2020 #sharetheroad #nplusone

I‚Äôm not sure I should have quit my day job. 
Two weeks ago, I returned home from visiting family in Canada. They‚Äôd given me a check for inheritance my aunt had left me

On the ferry ride back to the states I talked with my girlfriend, and we both decided I should put in my two weeks at my day job, the store I‚Äôd been at for the last nine years, take a portion of the money and try to draw comics full time. Take six months to dedicate to comics. See what happens. 
I‚Äôd been thinking of leaving that job for years, but I‚Äòd been dreaming of doing comics full time all my life. 
When I left for Canada three weeks ago, I had no concrete plans to quit, yet yesterday was my last day at that job.

I‚Äôm thrilled, overwhelmed, and frightened about what I‚Äôve done. 
Guess I better go make comics.

(Crossposted from matthewbogart.net) Several months ago, novelist, comedian, poet, storyteller, and president of Write Bloody Publishing, @derrickbrownpoetry wrote me with a plan. A friend of his was redesigning a huge building in a small town and wanted to turn it into a collection of shops designed by different creators. He wanted Derrick to dream big and design a bookstore.

Derrick told me his plan for Fascination Station. It was to be a train station, with a checkout counter modeled after Grand Central stations information kiosk. It would have cubby holes for reading, set into in the back wall designed like bunks on a train car. Large displays would be inset in arches showing landscapes rolling by. Travel posters advertising departure times for famous fictional destinations would hang on one wall, and shelves would roll away, so folding chairs could pull out from a secret compartment and an audience could watch authors read from the back of a full size caboose, as if they were on a whistle-stop tour.

It sounded wonderful, and Derrick wanted me to draw it.

While I make detailed 3D models for my comics, I‚Äôd never designed something like this. Something that was to become an actual physical place. Something that needed to fit in exact dimensions and be usable by flesh and blood people. It was a heck of a lot of fun, and the illustration came together in no time.

Fascination Station Book Store overhead view
An overhead view of Fascination Station ‚Äì a Write Bloody Bookstore
Sadly, things fell through. The Fascination Station only exists in these drawings.

But gosh does it make me want to go to a bookstore. So I think I will.

Acquainted with the Night

I have been one acquainted with the night.
I have walked out in rain‚Äîand back in rain.
I have outwalked the furthest city light.
I have looked down the saddest city lane.
I have passed by the watchman on his beat
And dropped my eyes, unwilling to explain.
I have stood still and stopped the sound of feet
When far away an interrupted cry
Came over houses from another street,
But not to call me back or say good-bye;
And further still at an unearthly height,
One luminary clock against the sky
Proclaimed the time was neither wrong nor right.
I have been one acquainted with the night.
‚Äî Robert Frost

Yesterday felt glorious! It was hovering just above freezing, but with the brilliant sun it felt really quite balmy! 

I had just spent a goodly amount time standing in a huge line at Costco to get groceries and had come up short on TP (though the cart was otherwise quite full)‚Ä¶ as I exited the building the feeling of the sun on my face hinted at what was coming.

As I pushed the cart through the slushy parking lot I was overwhelmed by a positive feeling! I felt grateful to have health, family, food to eat, and a planet that really is amenable to human life when compared to other options!

I was also grateful for all the snow and colder weather that preceded that moment which had the effect of sweetening that sunny-day-feeling!

#GiveThanks

When I lived in DC, every year there was a day I referred to as Tom Petty Day. It was a different day every year, and you never knew when it would be, but you know when it arrived ‚Äî a warm, sunny spring day when you first felt that the weather had turned a corner from sometimes warm/sometimes cold to consistently warm. In the sun and the warmth I‚Äôd realize Tom Petty Day was upon us, open the windows, hit play on Petty‚Äôs greatest hits CD and make things official with the first few notes of American Girl. I loved Tom Petty Day.
.
I was sad when I realized there is no Tom Petty Day in San Francisco; the weather just isn‚Äôt consistent or predictable enough; you never feel like the sun and warmth will stay for a more than a few days, certainly not for months. And so now I celebrate the occasional Tom Petty One Desperate Moment, when the weather is spectacular and the fog lifts, outside and in.
.
*well she was an American girl, raised on promises ....*

(Why Tom Petty? ‚ÄòCause I nearly wore that CD out spring semester freshman year of college, and as a result associate it strongly with a bright, warm DC spring day. Nothing more to it than that. Well, that and the fact that Tom Petty was awesome.)

APS is Arizona‚Äôs largest utility. It has a monopoly over the electricity business in much of the state. A monopoly over something everyone *has* to buy is a pretty good thing to have, if you‚Äôre into making money. And APS is *very* into making money. Half a *billion* dollars in profit last year alone.
...
But APS is never satisfied; not with hundreds of millions in profits. CEO Don Brandt personally took home millions. All for selling something people could only buy from them ‚Äî and that they *had* to buy.
... It gets hot in the summer in Arizona. Like, 115 degrees hot, daily, for long stretches. In weather like that, you need air conditioning, you need fans ‚Äî you need electricity. Or you die. ...
APS didn‚Äôt *need* the fifty bucks or so that 72-year-old Stephanie Pullman was a few days late in paying when APS decided to cut off her electricity on a 107 degree day. But APS sure *wanted* it.
...
A week later the county sheriff‚Äôs office found Stephanie in her home, dead of environmental heat exposure, her body already decomposing.
...
This will become more common, if we let it. Climate change will make hot days like that more common. An economy rigged to allow wealthy corporations to do whatever they want in the name of making a buck will lead to more millionaires like Don Brandt, too busy counting their cash to give a damn who dies when their electricity gets shut off. ...
If we let it.

T√§ss√§ meid√§n l√§hettil√§√§n Jaakon fiilikset kev√§√§n ensimm√§isen 10km matkan j√§lkeen Helsinki10:ll√§ pari viikkoa takaperin! üí™üòé // Greeting from our ambassador @jknuutila from his first 10k event this spring: üîú Preparing for the Helsinki Half Marathon - Helsinki 10 ‚úîÔ∏èI haven't raced a 10 K in years so I was a feeling a bit anxious on the race day. Thankfully the weather was warm, maybe even a bit too warm and the course was really familiar to me. ‚úîÔ∏èAfter a light warmup I lined up with the 57:30 pacers and was ready for the race. The sun was shining and I was feeling quite thirsty on the starting line. I figured that it was just the nerves and didn't think much of it at that time. The race started and I managed to keep a good even pace of 5:40 - 5:45 min/km for the first 5 km. ‚úîÔ∏èAt the start of 6 km my lower back started to ache and it affected by breathing rhythm. Luckily I was able to stretch my back while running and was able to continue but at the same time it meant that I slowed down to around 6 min/km pace for the kilometers 7 to 9. I picked up the pace on the final kilometer and crossed the finish line in 58:46. ‚úîÔ∏èFor the upcoming races I have to take a closer look at my fluid intake to make minimize the possibility of cramps or aches along the way. All in all Helsinki 10 was a well organized race with a fast route. I'll be on the starting line next year, that's for sure! üîôJaakko

The D&D gaming table is done. This was made for my buddy Mike, and the idea was to have a biiiiiig table that would fit 6 players and a DM  comfortably, but still fold away for storage when not in use. It features individual slide-in trays for each player's personal stuff, and plenty of space on the main tabletop for maps, etc. The legs fold up into the main body, the trays store underneath the tabletop, and the two halves collapse and latch together for storage.

The main body was made of Birch and Birch plywood, while the legs are made of solid Red Oak. Everything is stained dark walnut, with about 4 coats of semi-gloss lacquer finish, to provide protection and some spill-proofing. This is by far the largest thing I've built to date, and I learned a ton while doing it.

November is diabetes awareness month. EG was diagnosed in March of 2019. Technology helps us every day. We have replaced multiple daily finger sticks with a @dexcom continuous glucose monitor that gets replaced every ten days. Thanks to her new @myomnipod insulin pump that is replaced every three days, we no longer have to give her multiple daily injections. 3 glasses of whiskey in & feeling things:

If there is one thing this pandemic has reinforced for me, it is patience. Patience to wait for things to come; for the universe to provide.

This is a story about being patient.

I probably heard my first Frank Turner song about 8 years ago. He was just starting to get airplay in the US. He headlined Kegs & Eggs in 2013 but I missed it. I was finally finding my feet in Denver & healing after the collapse of a long term relationship. I was dating someone new for the first time &  things were going well. We were making plans, like buying tickets to @frankturner ‚Äôs fall tour that year.

But somewhere along the way that relationship fell apart. Differing love languages. A fear of commitment.

And so I found myself with 2 tickets but no one to go with. As the summer progressed someone new entered my life. I knew it was a bad idea. There were issues from the start. Those little red flags you ignore.

But before I knew it I was dating that new person. And one of the first real dates we had was the FT show I had tickets for. That night was about as perfect a night as I have ever had.

I fell in love that night. With both the girl and the music. One burned bright before exploding & breaking my heart. Which in the end was ok, because I had made it through most of my life without my heart truly being broken. And at the time that‚Äôs exactly what I needed.

The other love endured. FT‚Äôs music has gotten me through every high & low since.

That night at the show, I was so caught up in all of it that I missed buying a poster for the tour.

For 7 years, off & on, I‚Äôve been trying to buy that poster. Had never even seen one for sale.

Until a few weeks ago, when I was idly perusing eBay while stuck back home in TN. And there it was. Priced low enough to win (after a short bidding war). And now it‚Äôs mine.

If‚Äôs really just a piece of paper with an artist‚Äôs design on it. But to me it‚Äôs a connection to that night. That moment with someone new. That feeling of falling in love and knowing there is nothing you can do to stop it.

I haven‚Äôt felt that since.

But I have patience.

Several months ago at the start of the pandemic I bought a turntable; figuring vinyl would be a good habit to get into while stuck at home.

Of course, once it was delivered I needed a place to put it. So I started shopping for stands/consoles/vinyl storage.

Inspired by @brooklynndodger and @oldfashioneddanny‚Äòs dumpster find turned record console quarantine project, I went on the hunt on craigslist and found this art deco nightstand that looked to be the right size and fit. A lucky break.

It took a while to assemble the necessary tools, stain, supplies, etc. And to research how to strip the paint and refinish it since I‚Äôd never done that before.

The end result is honestly better than I was ever hoping for. I eyeballed the space where the two bottom drawers were when I bought the thing and wasn‚Äôt actually sure vinyl would fit. But it does, perfectly. Sawed right through the crossbar and made a perfect cube.

My dad was always a handy person who did most house projects himself. As an architect he designed and built the second story addition of the house I grew up in. I‚Äôd scare my mom by climbing the scaffolding and hanging out on the roof with him while he worked. He never let me get near the circular saw but I was always allowed to help mix concrete.

I haven‚Äôt often had much reason or need to do that type of stuff on my own as an adult. But it feels really good to take an idea, visualize the result, gather the necessary tools and knowledge, and execute the vision into something you‚Äôre proud of. Highly recommended.

It‚Äôs made for a very fun weekend project and a nice addition to the room. Now I just need my backordered speakers to arrive...UPDATE: Found the speakers on sale for a similar price at another retailer, arriving FRIDAY. YAY!

It took several months but the day finally arrived today and the universe reiterated once again that this press was meant to be mine.

Once I arrived at the Depot everything came together: 

Convinced the driver to turn around from another delivery to come right away before the folks at the crane company across the street left for the day.

The crane folks weren‚Äôt even supposed to still be there as they had sold the property to a developer and had planned to be moved out by the 1st.

Within about 30 minutes they had a forklift over and my press down the ramp and at the door. Only hiccup was not having a pallet jack at the ready (currently on loan to a board member).

Luckily they were able to grab one of those too and now the press is where she will stay for a bit.

Meet Gertrude.

She‚Äôs gonna rest at the Depot for a bit while I am back home in TN for the winter but come spring I think we are gonna get on just great.

12 or so years ago a young, friendly, and slightly obnoxious grey and white tuxedo cat showed up on our porch in TN, not long after I had come home from a failed attempt at living and working overseas.

He had a pink collar and was very affectionate and happy. And most importantly, night after night, he just stayed on the porch. He would curl up on this rocking chair, no bigger than the gourd sitting there now.

He caused a ruckus too by killing and gutting a couple of mourning doves, much to my mom‚Äôs horror. But then we‚Äôve always had cats so having kills brought to us has never been surprising (except the live snakes, whoo boy).

Since he wouldn‚Äôt leave we began to feed him. My mom had already taken in two stray cats but eventually she said we could bring him in and she would pay to take him to the vet and get checked out.

We did our due diligence and called shelters and checked if he was chipped. But it was the start of the recession and lots of animals were abandoned. His previous owners were gone.

And so, he came into the house, made friends with the other two cats, and was given the name Brutus, because he brute forced his way into our home.

I was still dealing with the loss of a previous cat, who died under the worst circumstances (falling out a window in Vienna and suffering for a week as vets tried their best to save him).

But it was clear that Brutus was not going to take no for an answer and my mom made it clear that when I moved back to Colorado he would have to go with me.

And so he did.

I was really worried about moving him back with me to TN. I bought a fancy carrier and a thundershirt and calming spray. The first part of the trip was pretty rough. But we made it.

And in the end I realized that home for him wasn‚Äôt the apartment we shared in Denver. Home has always been wherever I am. He is the most affectionate cat I have ever owned. He‚Äôs my buddy, my best friend, and I desperately wish he could live forever.

At least right now, we are here and working through this rough patch together. This is, for both of us, our ancestral home. Where it all began. And where the next phase begins.

Love you Brutus.

Goodbye Kiwi.

You were not mine; but you were my favorite. You were a houseguest through many lonely Thanksgivings, an exuberant greeter whenever I came over, a lover of walks and the outdoors, and completely devoted to your humans. The minute your leash was reached for you lost all control of your excitement and it was glorious. You had a wiggly butt that just would not quit. You always exhibited the utmost control when waiting for permission to eat, even though it was so, so hard for you.

You wanted desperately to be friends with Brutus but learned quickly to give him space when a guest at our place. You forgot this lesson one time and it nearly cost you an eye. Eventually he let you sleep a mere foot away from him on the couch. He tolerated you, which is high praise from a cat.

You cheerfully accompanied me all the way up a 14er once, though you were not enthused once we got to the summit. You enjoyed meeting the bighorn sheep. We were both very thirsty by the time we got down.

You lived a full life and had two companions that loved you deeply. And many more who admired you and cared for you. You were the cutest dog in the world with the most expressive eyebrow muscles imaginable. The faces you would pull brought smiles to everyone.

I am so very sad you are gone, but I am so happy for the time I got to spend with you, and the trust your humans placed in me in letting me  dogsit you over the years.

I am so sorry @mallorybeesknees and @tomac139 for your loss. You gave her a wonderful life and home. She was the bestest doggo. The world is less bright right now without her in it. I will miss her dearly.

Goodbye Brutus.

We cuddled as best we could in the middle of the night and I cried and he tried to give me the weakest of headbuts but his strength is all gone.

This morning I held him in my lap in the sun one last time, then I carried him around the yard so he could hear the birds and look at the squirrels.

Then we went to the vet and I held him in my lap and looked into his eyes until he was gone.

He was the best cat in the world. My best buddy. I really don‚Äôt know what I will do without him.

I love you Brutus.

I used to love St. Paddy‚Äôs Day. I guess I still do. But it is always tinged with sadness now. I‚Äôve lost too much during this time of year. Best friends, relationships, pets. March is just a bad month for me. Unlucky.

So here‚Äôs to those we‚Äôve lost. Those who left. The ones who died. The ones who fought for independence. My ancestors that came over on a ship and started a new life, which eventually led to me. My best friend who made a bad decision 17 years ago. My cat, who deserved so much more time.

To those you‚Äôve lost too.

Absolutely destroyed by this loss today. Sometimes you just don‚Äôt realize who your heroes were until they are gone. You don‚Äôt hear the stories of their compassion or kindness or truth until after.
We lost an incredible voice for good today. The world is much darker now. Be kind, be compassionate. Take someone to dinner tonight or cook for them. Be curious of everyone you meet and always interested in who they really are. RIP Anthony Bourdain.

Still struggling to process. Still gutted. How is it possible to feel so sad yet also so overjoyed at what he gave us with the time he had? How do you look directly at someone who has had it harder than you but survived and thrived and was doing what they were put here to do while knowing that you are nowhere close to achieving the same thing. Even if you can see a possible path forward, how do you conquer fear and pain the way he did for so long? And to know that even in doing so, it will never be enough. There is no end state of happiness and fulfillment. There is always the peaks and valleys until both run out and the race is over. On days like this everything feels impossible but somehow possible all at the same time. It‚Äôs paralyzing. Picture via @voguemagazine

My grandpa had over 30 bonsai trees on shelves on his back patio when I was a kid. He died when I was young and none of those bonsai made their way to me. As far as I know they were all tossed. Which is a real shame, because it‚Äôs a very appealing art form that probably could have affected me in positive ways when I was younger.
Tonight I watched an expert put this bonsai composition together in a matter of 90 minutes, all while delivering a lecture on the art and process of bonsai at the same time. An impressive feat. Perhaps I never would have appreciated it when I was young, but now with the benefit of nostalgia, I have a desire to explore those roots, both real and metaphorical. I don‚Äôt know if I have the patience or dedication yet to learn, but I‚Äôm willing to try for the personal growth and meditative benefits alone.

Do things happen for a reason? I don‚Äôt know. Ask me again a year from now and I might answer differently.
üá∫üá∏
I think we make things happen, whether consciously or unconsciously. Every time I visit the South, I get a little nostalgic, maybe even homesick. About a year ago that led me to a wonderful website (and now podcast) called @bittersoutherner. I‚Äôve been supporting and reading it ever since. I even joined their member‚Äôs only Facebook group, which is where I learned about President Carter‚Äôs Sunday School.
üá∫üá∏
Fast forward to this weekend. I‚Äôm on my way back home to take care of my mom and while planning this idea just popped up: what if I could grab a car and drive down to Plains, GA for the service?
üá∫üá∏
Now I‚Äôm no Christian. In fact this might be my first ever visit to Sunday School. But I really needed the reminder that good people have been President. And continue to do good. And there are good Christians too. Too often, growing up in the South, I focused on how people used religion for their own selfish purposes. Or as a reason to hate. I still have plenty of issues with organized religion. But the ideas, man, the ideas are good!
üá∫üá∏
Would that everyone could hear Jimmy Carter speak about these ideals. Would that everyone could follow his example in the way he has led his life. He asked us today if we would make America better, just by helping a neighbor, or a friend, or a family member, and I hope we can rise to his challenge, now more than ever. üá∫üá∏üá∫üá∏üá∫üá∏

London: You beautiful, mad, wonderful city. I‚Äôve seen more of you this trip than ever before, from rolling hills and fields in muddy commons to back alleys covered in wall to wall street art. The diversity of experiences and people are like no where else in the world I‚Äôve been.

None of this should work. Many might say it barely does. But day after day of riding the trains and the underground and seeing people go about their day proves otherwise. Somehow, through centuries and logistics and technology and good will, it just does.

There was sun and rain, top level and non-league football, and amazing art both on the street and in the galleries. Great food, both on the go and when sat in a pub. 
And always, good friendship and conversation. I couldn‚Äôt have made this trip without the hospitality of Jade and especially her mom, who gave me a place to stay and home cooked meals and most importantly fresh coffee every morning. I‚Äôm lucky to have such a good friend and she‚Äôs lucky to have such a great family.

There‚Äôs only one word that comes to mind whenever I visit London, and this trip has been no different: Fantastic. #travel #london

Beauty is a choice.

I think we sometimes forget that. Our society incentivizes us to judge constantly, to always see the negative, to tear down anyone or anything that dares to rise above the fray.

But it‚Äôs still our choice to participate. To comment or tweet or be rude to someone just because we can. It‚Äôs so easy to resort to ugliness.

This Fall has been the worst weather I think I‚Äôve ever experienced in Colorado. Snowstorms came early and haven‚Äôt stopped coming. The last one was the biggest in 25 years. Tonight it snowed yet again. Not for long, but long enough to really drive home how shitty it‚Äôs been.

We haven‚Äôt even hit December and it already feels like we‚Äôve had more snow than entire years previous to this. It‚Äôs disheartening. It‚Äôs hard to get around the city. It‚Äôs hard to even want to leave the warmth of home.

Tonight I was determined to go out anyway. To see good friends and to imbibe good drinks and to have good conversations that probably won‚Äôt change the world but at least might make both participants think just a little bit deeper than before.

Sure we commiserated about the weather. Hard not to. It‚Äôs easy to complain. But on the way home I chose to walk a few extra blocks out of my way to the park nearby to take this picture.

With the snow covered field in the foreground and the skyline of the city I love standing against the horizon, it was easy to stop, in the cold, with wet snow creeping into my shoes, and choose to see the beauty of this moment on a cold, snowy night. Just the beauty of the snow and the lights of the city against the dark sky.

These moments are always there, all around us. We just have to stop and choose to see them. To choose them over the ugliness.

Beauty is a choice.

It has been a decade. If you are reading this, we‚Äôve survived. That‚Äôs something. Some of my friends haven‚Äôt.

When I look back it‚Äôs a bit daunting to consider how much has changed. The whole decade feels like two halves.

At the end of 2009, I had finally managed to move to Denver. But it was on the back of a pretty major failure at a job/career I thought I‚Äôd be really good at. I‚Äôd also just taken my mom on an amazing trip of a lifetime to Vienna, but even that was bittersweet as it was also the beginning of the end of the relationship that had brought me back there.

In the early part of this decade, I had to start over from scratch. And that‚Äôs what I did. I struggled but found work. I went out and made new lifelong friends. I even fell into new relationships, which, while they didn‚Äôt last, taught me the importance of communication, listening, how to have your heart broken, and more importantly how to mend it and how to be comfortable being alone.

The first half of the decade I was filled with hope for the future of the world and our country, but pretty down on my own life and future.

Everything flipped in the latter half. While I‚Äôm increasingly pessimistic about the world and the rise of everything awful in the last four years, I‚Äôve been much luckier in my personal life. I‚Äôve grown as a person. I‚Äôve traveled to places I‚Äôd only dreamed of. I made new lifelong friends. I found communities of creative, like-minded people that I can‚Äôt wait to engage with more in the new decade.

I‚Äôve never been more excited or terrified of what comes next. I have a (rough) plan. Execution will be in the details. I‚Äôve become more flexible, more calm, more focused, and sometimes I almost feel ready for the challenges ahead.

Here‚Äôs to 2020 being the start of an amazing decade for all of us, full of love and challenges and successes and failures and bouncebacks and survival. Happy New Year!

As his bloodies got increasingly more complex, almost architectural, his friends realized, too late, that his tenuous grip on reality was slipping.

The increasingly Jenga-like structures, built higher and higher with little regard to stability, dietary needs, or traditional norms, were lauded for their creativity and brazenness.

But underneath, were they a cry for help? Was the foundation of these triumphant tributes to mornings at the pub (watching soccer with friends while nursing the ultimate hangover cure drink) rotten to the core?

No one knew for sure. Nor could they stop it. They could only watch as his alcoholic towers of Babel were built higher and higher, watching with both dread and anticipation of their eventual collapse.

#bloodymary #bloodies #quarantine

This weekend was the first time I really pined for a return to normalcy. I have been very fortunate in that my life and job at home had to change very little to support our new reality. But while the logistics have been easy, the emotional side has not been.

Since before this quarantine started, I have been worried about pretty much only one thing: my mom, who is in the high risk category for the virus; isolated at home in TN.

Sometime earlier this week my mom fell. This is a regular occurrence. Only this time she was unable to get back up. Normally, Meals on Wheels would stop by and she would receive help. But they only come once a week now, on Fridays.

It took me two days to realize something was wrong after multiple unanswered messages. We called in a wellness check and the police found her on the floor near the front door.

She‚Äôs in the hospital now and seemingly ok. But she‚Äôs going to be there for at least a week. And after that she has to go to a long term care facility for rehab.

This means that the nightmare I‚Äôve been having from the start of all this has suddenly become significantly more likely. The two places I wanted to make sure she avoided are now the two places she has to be to recover from her fall. The virus has been spreading mercilessly through nursing homes and other facilities. If my mom catches it there is very little chance of her surviving.

I am scared.

I really, really hope I get to see my mom again. I hate that I can‚Äôt go visit, can‚Äôt support her, basically have to just sit here and worry (which I know doesn‚Äôt help). On Friday, I went down to Castlewood Canyon State Park. I needed not just to go somewhere new and be in nature but I needed someplace calming and serene to help cope with all the uncertainty. Hanging out with 55 million year old rocks helped for a bit.

Time seems to be passing really damn slowly right now. I know all of us are going through a lot. The daily onslaught of news and the amount of uncertainty about the future can be completely overwhelming. I‚Äôm sharing what I‚Äôm going through because I think it‚Äôs important to share and ask for help when you need it. No one should have to go through any of this alone.
Today it got too hot. Glad tomorrow should be cooler. Masks in the summer are gonna suuuuuck.

TBT to this Monday when I spent 8 wonderful hours at this park.

That morning I got off to a slow start. And pretty early on I just became overwhelmed with sadness. Not over anything in particular. Maybe over everything. My mom. This pandemic. The way people treat each other. The horribleness and brutality that continues to be inflicted on black and marginalized people. The lack of social connection. The selfishness, privilege, entitlement, and greed seemingly always on display. The sheer stupidity of our ‚Äúleaders‚Äù. It was a lot. And it was clear I was going to have to sit with that sadness for a bit. But that didn‚Äôt mean I had to stay home.

I made my way out to the park with no real plan. Just some water and a snack. A cursory glance at the map at the trailhead was enough to set off. The falls seemed like a reachable destination and turnaround point.

Staunton is a beautiful place. Easy to hike and with lots of gentle elevation change for a decent workout. I made it to the falls in about two hours and hung out there for a bit watching climbers rappel down the rock-face.

By 5:15pm, I decided I could push on to the overlook, which put me high above the falls for a completely different perspective. From there I discovered a shortcut back to the pond.

My final good decision was refusing to take the same trail back to the parking lot, instead veering off on a longer trail that looped up to another dazzling view and then past an old mill. Friends I had over an hour on that trail of complete solitude and it was joyous. Not another living soul nearby. Hard to explain how much I needed that given our solitary current lifestyle. But for an hour I didn‚Äôt have to think about anyone not wearing a mask or being an asshole or anything as no one passed me on the trail.

By 7:20pm I had made it to the mill and challenged the sun to a race to see who would arrive first: me back at the parking lot or the sun at it‚Äôs destination on the horizon (the sun won, but it was close). The last gift nature had to give me was a fox that loped straight across my path at the parking lot, seeking out a dinner of scraps beneath the picnic tables.

And I realized I was no longer sad.

A few pics of animal friends I met at Staunton State Park on Memorial Day. Also a gnarly gothic looking stump. Not pictured: a dazzlingly blue little bird that flew away before I could capture a zoomed in and slightly blurry pic.

I made this 6 years ago.
It was an extra lockup I had a bit of time to make in a letterpress workshop I was taking over a weekend, taught by @rickgriffith

At the time the Ferguson protests were still raging and I was heartbroken seeing St. Louis, a city I had called home for 5 years, devolve into chaos. I was heartbroken over Michael Brown, a black man I did not know, losing his life unnecessarily. I was heartbroken at the comments and media coverage all bent on justifying a murder.

I spent every night following the coverage on social media. Arguing with people who didn‚Äôt understand. Trying to get through to friends who weren‚Äôt ready to. Trying to find my voice and my place to speak out, while also reconciling my privilege and status in this corrupt system we‚Äôve built.

I learned. I listened. I expanded my exposure to black and marginalized voices and I sat with the pain and suffering they voiced. I empathized as much as I could.

I took action too. I joined the marches and protests here. I took the print above and fashioned it into a protest sign. I lay on the street and played dead to block traffic.

And in the end, nothing changed. Here we are, 6 years later and if anything it‚Äôs gotten worse. Some days I fear the only option is to run, an immense privilege.

But I also see so much good being shared now. Mutual aid groups. Organizing. Outspoken activists. And, best of all, this shared sense that this time, maybe everyone I know gets it. I‚Äôm not arguing with friends now. The people I know are using their voices, sharing resources, boosting marginalized voices, trying to help however they can. We are not perfect and we all still have to reckon with our privilege and comfort and the gravitational pull of that. It‚Äôs so much easier to sit behind a screen and be safe. Especially during a pandemic.

I hope we all challenge ourselves to do more. To be willing to hit the streets. To risk the tear gas and rubber bullets. Because the thing about equality is it really does affect all of us. We‚Äôre all being held back by these backwards views. We can‚Äôt play it safe anymore. Our whole country is at risk. Let‚Äôs not choose the warmth of the fire as it burns down around us.

Unexpectedly spending the next several weeks where I grew up, so time for some origin stories:
1986. We would drive down the mountain (usually in my mom's beige Volvo station wagon) to this Pizza Hut for family dinners. Back when you ate their pizzas with a knife and fork, like a gentleman, with a white tablecloth underneath.
To the left of the entrance they had a stand up arcade version of Super Mario Bros. I quickly became obsessed. I played it every time we went. I dreamt about it. The music haunted me.
Despite my obsession, when pressed, I asked for an Atari 7800 for my birthday? Xmas? Not sure that year.
It would be three more long years before I saved up enough to buy an NES of my own and finally reach the minus world.
